# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anthropologist
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anthropologist/academy] An **academy** (Attic Greek: Ἀκαδήμεια; Koine Greek: Ἀκαδημία) is an institution of tertiary education.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The name traces back to Plato's school of philosophy, founded c.
[src:anthropologist/academy] 386 BC at Akademia, a sanctuary of Athena, the goddess of wisdom and skill, north of Athens, Greece.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Royal Spanish Academy defines an academy as a scientific, literary or artistic society established with public authority and as a teaching establishment, public or private, of a professional, artistic, technical or simply practical nature.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The word comes from the *Academy* in ancient Greece, which derives from the Athenian hero, *Akademos*.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Outside the city walls of Athens, the gymnasium was made famous by Plato as a center of learning.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The sacred space, dedicated to the goddess of wisdom, Athena, had formerly been an olive grove, hence the expression "the groves of Academe".
[src:anthropologist/academy] In these gardens, the philosopher Plato conversed with followers.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Plato developed his sessions into a method of teaching philosophy and in 387 BC, established what is known today as the Old Academy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] By extension, *academia* has come to mean the accumulation, development and transmission of knowledge across generations as well as its practitioners and transmitters.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the 17th century, British, Italian and French scholars used the term to describe types of institutions of higher learning.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Before *Akademia* was a school, and even before Cimon enclosed its precincts with a wall, it contained a sacred grove of olive trees dedicated to Athena, the goddess of wisdom, outside the city walls of ancient Athens.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The archaic name for the site was *Hekademia*, which by classical times evolved into *Akademia* and was explained, at least as early as the beginning of the 6th century BC, by linking it to an Athenian hero, a legendary "Akademos".
[src:anthropologist/academy] The site of *Akademia* was sacred to Athena and other immortals.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Plato's immediate successors as "scholarch" of *Akademia* were Speusippus (347–339 BC), Xenocrates (339–314 BC), Polemon (314–269 BC), Crates (c.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Later scholarchs include Lacydes of Cyrene, Carneades, Clitomachus, and Philo of Larissa ("the last undisputed head of the Academy").
[src:anthropologist/academy] Other notable members of *Akademia* include Aristotle, Heraclides Ponticus, Eudoxus of Cnidus, Philip of Opus, Crantor, and Antiochus of Ascalon.
[src:anthropologist/academy] After a lapse during the early Roman occupation, *Akademia* was refounded as a new institution of some outstanding Platonists of late antiquity who called themselves "successors" (*diadochoi*, but of Plato) and presented themselves as an uninterrupted tradition reaching back to Plato.
[src:anthropologist/academy] However, there cannot have actually been any geographical, institutional, economic or personal continuity with the original Academy in the new organizational entity.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The emperor Justinian ceased the school's funding in AD 529, a date that is often cited as the end of Antiquity.
[src:anthropologist/academy] According to the sole witness, the historian Agathias, its remaining members looked for protection under the rule of Sassanid king Khosrau I in his capital at Ctesiphon, carrying with them precious scrolls of literature and philosophy, and to a lesser degree of science.
[src:anthropologist/academy] After a peace treaty between the Persian and the Byzantine empire in 532 guaranteed their personal security (an early document in the history of freedom of religion), some members found sanctuary in the pagan stronghold of Harran, near Edessa.
[src:anthropologist/academy] One of the last leading figures of this group was Simplicius, a pupil of Damascius, the last head of the Athenian school.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It has been speculated that *Akademia* did not altogether disappear.
[src:anthropologist/academy] After his exile, Simplicius (and perhaps some others), may have travelled to Harran, near Edessa.
[src:anthropologist/academy] From there, the students of an academy-in-exile could have survived into the 9th century, long enough to facilitate the Arabic revival of the Neoplatonist commentary tradition in Baghdad.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In ancient Greece, after the establishment of the original Academy, Plato's colleagues and pupils developed spin-offs of his method.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Arcesilaus, a Greek student of Plato established the Middle Academy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Carneades, another student, established the New Academy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 335 BC, Aristotle refined the method with his own theories and established the Lyceum in another gymnasium.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Musaeum, Serapeum and library of Alexandria Egypt was frequented by intellectuals from Africa, Europe and Asia studying various aspects of philosophy, language and mathematics.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The University of Timbuktu was a medieval university in Timbuktu, present-day Mali, which comprised three schools: the Mosque of Djinguereber, the Mosque of Sidi Yahya, and the Mosque of Sankore.
[src:anthropologist/academy] During its zenith, the university had an average attendance of around 25,000 students within a city of around 100,000 people.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In China a higher education institution Shang Xiang was founded by Shun in the Youyu era before the 21st century BC.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Imperial Central Academy at Nanjing, founded in 258, was a result of the evolution of Shang Xiang and it became the first comprehensive institution combining education and research and was divided into five faculties in 470, which later became Nanjing University.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the 8th century another kind of institution of learning emerged, named Shuyuan, which were generally privately owned.
[src:anthropologist/academy] There were thousands of Shuyuan recorded in ancient times.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The degrees from them varied from one to another and those advanced Shuyuan such as Bailudong Shuyuan and Yuelu Shuyuan (later become Hunan University) can be classified as higher institutions of learning.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Taxila or Takshashila, in ancient India, modern-day Pakistan, was an early centre of learning, near present-day Islamabad in the city of Taxila.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It is considered one of the ancient universities of the world.
[src:anthropologist/academy] According to scattered references which were only fixed a millennium later it may have dated back to at least the 5th century BC.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Some scholars date Takshashila's existence back to the 6th century BC.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The school consisted of several monasteries without large dormitories or lecture halls where the religious instruction was most likely still provided on an individualistic basis.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Takshashila is described in some detail in later Jātaka tales, written in Sri Lanka around the 5th century AD.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It became a noted centre of learning at least several centuries BC, and continued to attract students until the destruction of the city in the 5th century AD.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Takshashila is perhaps best known because of its association with Chanakya.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The famous treatise Arthashastra (Sanskrit for The knowledge of Economics) by Chanakya, is said to have been composed in Takshashila itself.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Chanakya (or Kautilya), the Maurya Emperor Chandragupta and the Ayurvedic healer Charaka studied at Taxila.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Generally, a student entered Takshashila at the age of sixteen.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Vedas and the Eighteen Arts, which included skills such as archery, hunting, and elephant lore, were taught, in addition to its law school, medical school, and school of military science.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Nalanda was established in the 5th century AD in Bihar, India.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It was founded in 427 in northeastern India, not far from what is today the southern border of Nepal.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It survived until 1197 when it was set upon, destroyed and burnt by the marauding forces of Ikhtiyar Uddin Muhammad bin Bakhtiyar Khilji.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It was devoted to Buddhist studies, but it also trained students in fine arts, medicine, mathematics, astronomy, politics and the art of war.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The center had eight separate compounds, 10 temples, meditation halls, classrooms, lakes and parks.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It had a nine-story library where monks meticulously copied books and documents so that individual scholars could have their own collections.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It had dormitories for students, perhaps a first for an educational institution, housing 10,000 students in the university's heyday and providing accommodation for 2,000 professors.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Nalanda University attracted pupils and scholars from Korea, Japan, China, Tibet, Indonesia, Persia and Turkey.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The geographical position of Persia allowed it to absorb cultural influences and ideas from both west and east.
[src:anthropologist/academy] This include the spread of the Greek form of schools in the new Hellenistic cities built in Persia after the invasion of Alexander the Great.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Under the Sasanians, Syriac became an important language of the administration and intellectuals, rivaling Greek.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Several cities developed centers of higher learning in the Sasanian Empire, including Mosul, al-Hira, and Harran (famous for the Pythagorean School of the Sabians).
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Grand School was the main center of learning in the Persian capital Ctesiphon, but little is known about it.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Perhaps the most famous center of learning in Persia was the Academy of Gundishapur, teaching medicine, mathematics, astronomy, and logic.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The academy was later instrumental in founding the Muslim city of Baghdad as a center of learning, and serving as the model for the first Muslim hospital (*bimaristan*) at Damascus.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Founded in Fes, University of Al-Karaouine in the 9th century and in Cairo, Al-Azhar University in the 10th century, and in Mali, the University of Timbuktu in about 1100.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Mustansiriya Madrasah in Baghdad, Iraq, was established in 1227 as a madrasah by the Abbasid Caliph al-Mustansir.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Its library had an initial collection of 80,000 volumes, given by the Caliph.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The collection was said to have grown to 400,000 volumes.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In Europe, the academy dates to the ancient Greeks and Romans in the pre-Christian era.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Newer universities were founded in the 12th and 13th centuries, and the European institution of academia took shape.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Monks and priests moved out of monasteries to cathedral cities and other towns where they opened the first schools dedicated to advanced study.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The most notable of these new schools were in Bologna and Salerno, Naples, Salamanca, Paris, Oxford and Cambridge, while others were opened throughout Europe.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The seven liberal arts—the Trivium (Grammar, Rhetoric, and Logic), and the Quadrivium (Arithmetic, Geometry, Music, and Astronomy)—had been codified in late antiquity.
[src:anthropologist/academy] This was the basis of the curriculum in Europe until newly available Arabic texts and the works of Aristotle became more available in Europe in the 12th century.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It remained in place even after the new scholasticism of the School of Chartres and the encyclopedic work of Thomas Aquinas, until the humanism of the 15th and 16th centuries opened new studies of arts and sciences.
[src:anthropologist/academy] With the Neoplatonist revival that accompanied the revival of humanist studies, *academia* took on newly vivid connotations.
[src:anthropologist/academy] During the Florentine Renaissance, Cosimo de' Medici took a personal interest in the new Platonic Academy that he determined to re-establish in 1439, centered on the marvellous promise shown by the young Marsilio Ficino.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Cosimo had been inspired by the arrival at the otherwise ineffective Council of Florence of Gemistos Plethon, who seemed a dazzling figure to the Florentine intellectuals.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1462 Cosimo gave Ficino a villa at Careggi for the academy's use, situated where Cosimo could see it from his own villa, and drop by for visits.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The academy remained a wholly informal group, but one which had a great influence on Renaissance Neo-Platonism.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In Rome, after unity was restored following the Western Schism, humanist circles, cultivating philosophy and searching out and sharing ancient texts tended to gather where there was access to a library.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Vatican Library was not coordinated until 1475 and was never catalogued or widely accessible: not all popes looked with satisfaction at gatherings of unsupervised intellectuals.
[src:anthropologist/academy] At the head of this movement for renewal in Rome was Cardinal Bessarion, whose house from the mid-century was the centre of a flourishing academy of Neoplatonic philosophy and a varied intellectual culture.
[src:anthropologist/academy] His valuable Greek as well as Latin library (eventually bequeathed to the city of Venice after he withdrew from Rome) was at the disposal of the academicians.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Bessarion, in the latter years of his life, retired from Rome to Ravenna, but he left behind him ardent adherents of the classic philosophy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] He was a worshipper not merely of the literary and artistic form, but also of the ideas and spirit of classic paganism, which made him appear a condemner of Christianity and an enemy of the Church.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In his academy every member assumed a classical name.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The prisoners begged so earnestly for mercy, and with such protestations of repentance, that they were pardoned.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Letonian academy, however, collapsed.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In Naples, the *Quattrocento* academy founded by Alfonso of Aragon and guided by Antonio Beccadelli was the *Porticus Antoniana*, later known as the *Accademia Pontaniana*, after Giovanni Pontano.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The 16th century saw at Rome a great increase of literary and aesthetic academies, more or less inspired by the Renaissance, all of which assumed, as was the fashion, odd and fantastic names.
[src:anthropologist/academy] We learn from various sources the names of many such institutes; as a rule, they soon perished and left no trace.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the 1520s came the *Accademia degli Intronati*, for the encouragement of theatrical representations.
[src:anthropologist/academy] There were also the academy of the "Vignaiuoli", or "Vinegrowers" (1530), and the *Accademia della Virtù* (1542), founded by Claudio Tolomei under the patronage of Cardinal Ippolito de' Medici.
[src:anthropologist/academy] These were followed by a new academy in the "Orti" or Farnese gardens.
[src:anthropologist/academy] There were also the academies of the "Intrepidi" (1560), the "Animosi" (1576), and the "Illuminati" (1598); this last, founded by the Marchesa Isabella Aldobrandini Pallavicino.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Towards the middle of the 16th century there were also the academy of the "Notti Vaticane", or "Vatican Nights", founded by St.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Charles Borromeo; an "Accademia di Diritto civile e canonico", and another of the university scholars and students of philosophy (Accademia Eustachiana).
[src:anthropologist/academy] As a rule these academies, all very much alike, were merely circles of friends or clients gathered around a learned man or wealthy patron, and were dedicated to literary pastimes rather than methodical study.
[src:anthropologist/academy] They fitted in, nevertheless, with the general situation and were in their own way one element of the historical development.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Despite their empirical and fugitive character, they helped to keep up the general esteem for literary and other studies.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Cardinals, prelates, and the clergy in general were most favourable to this movement, and assisted it by patronage and collaboration.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The private Accademia degli Incamminati set up later in the century in Bologna by the Carracci brothers was also extremely influential, and with the Accademia di San Luca of Rome (founded 1593) helped to confirm the use of the term for these institutions.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Gradually academies began to specialize on particular topics (arts, language, sciences) and began to be founded and funded by the kings and other sovereigns (few republics had an academy).
[src:anthropologist/academy] And, mainly, since 17th century academies spread throughout Europe.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the 17th century the tradition of literary-philosophical academies, as circles of friends gathering around learned patrons, was continued in Italy; the "Umoristi" (1611), the "Fantastici (1625), and the "Ordinati", founded by Cardinal Dati and Giulio Strozzi.
[src:anthropologist/academy] About 1700 were founded the academies of the "Infecondi", the "Occulti", the "Deboli", the "Aborigini", the "Immobili", the "Accademia Esquilina", and others.
[src:anthropologist/academy] During the 18th century many Italian cities established similar philosophical and scientific academies.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Académie de peinture et de sculpture in Paris, established by the monarchy in 1648 (later renamed) was the most significant of the artistic academies, running the famous Salon exhibitions from 1725.
[src:anthropologist/academy] A fundamental feature of academic discipline in the artistic academies was regular practice in making accurate drawings from antiquities, or from casts of antiquities, on the one hand, and on the other, in deriving inspiration from the other fount, the human form.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Students assembled in sessions drawing the draped and undraped human form, and such drawings, which survive in the tens of thousands from the 17th through the 19th century, are termed ***académies*** in French.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Similar institutions were often established for other arts: Rome had the Accademia di Santa Cecilia for music from 1585; Paris had the Académie Royale de Musique from 1669 and the Académie Royale d'Architecture from 1671.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1582 five Florentine literati gathered and founded the Accademia della Crusca to demonstrate and conserve the beauty of the Florentine vernacular tongue, modelled upon the authors of the Trecento.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The main instrument to do so was the *Vocabolario degli Accademici della Crusca*.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Crusca long remained a private institution, criticizing and opposing the official Accademia Fiorentina.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The first institution inspired by the Crusca was the Fruitbearing Society for German language, which existed from 1617 to 1680.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Crusca inspired Richelieu to found in 1634 the analogous Académie française with the task of acting as an official authority on the French language, charged with publishing the official dictionary of that language.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The following year the Académie received letters patent from King Louis XIII as the only recognized academy for French language.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In its turn the state established Académie was the model for the *Real Academia Española* (founded in 1713) and the Swedish Academy (1786), which are the ruling bodies of their respective languages and editors of major dictionaries.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It also was the model for the Russian Academy, founded in 1783, which afterwards merged into the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:anthropologist/academy] After the short-lived Academia Secretorum Naturae of Naples, the first academy exclusively devoted to sciences was the Accademia dei Lincei founded in 1603 in Rome, particularly focused on natural sciences.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1657 some students of Galileo founded the Accademia del Cimento (Academy of Experiment) in Florence, focused on physics and astronomy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The foundation of academy was funded by Prince Leopoldo and Grand Duke Ferdinando II de' Medici.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1652 was founded the Academia Naturae Curiosorum by four physicians.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1677, Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor, recognised the society and in 1687 he gave it the epithet *Leopoldina*, with which is internationally famous., p.
[src:anthropologist/academy] 7–8; So, it became the academy of sciences for the whole Holy Roman Empire.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1662 Charles II of England signed a Royal Charter which created the "Royal Society of London", then "Royal Society of London for the Improvement of Natural Knowledge".
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1666 Colbert gathered a small group of scholars to found a scientific society in Paris.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The first 30 years of the academy's existence were relatively informal, since no statutes had as yet been laid down for the institution.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In contrast to Royal Society, the academy was founded as an organ of government.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1699, Louis XIV gave the academy its first rules and named it Académie royale des sciences.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Although Prussia was a member of Holy Roman Empire, in 1700 Prince-elector Frederick III of Brandenburg founded its own Prussian Academy of Sciences upon the advice of Gottfried Leibniz, who was appointed president.
[src:anthropologist/academy] This kind of academy lost importance after the university reform begun with the foundation of the University of Berlin, when universities were provided with laboratories and clinics, and were charged with doing experimental research.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Academic societies or learned societies began as groups of academics who worked together or presented their work to each other.
[src:anthropologist/academy] These informal groups later became organized and in many cases state-approved.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Membership was restricted, usually requiring approval of the current members and often total membership was limited to a specific number.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Royal Society founded in 1660 was the first such academy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1720, King John V of Portugal approved the founding and gave royal patronage to the Royal Academy of Portuguese History which had been meeting informally, since 1717, under the sponsorship of the 4th Count of Ericeira.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The American Academy of Arts and Sciences was begun in 1780 by many of the same people prominent in the American Revolution.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Academic societies served both as a forum to present and publish academic work, the role now served by academic publishing, and as a means to sponsor research and support academics, a role they still serve.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Membership in academic societies is still a matter of prestige in modern academia.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Starting at the end of the 16th century in the Holy Roman Empire, France, Poland and Denmark, many Knight academies were established to prepare the aristocratic youth for state and military service.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Many of them lately turned into gymnasiums, but some of them were transformed into true military academies.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Royal Danish Military Academy began to educate all officers for the Royal Danish Army by request of King Frederick IV in 1713.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The École Militaire was founded by Louis XV in 1750 with the aim of creating an academic college for cadet officers from poor families.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The construction began in 1752, but the school did not open until 1760.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Theresian Military Academy was founded on 14 December 1751 by Maria Theresa of Austria.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Per year the academy accepted 100 noblemen and 100 commoners to start their education there.
[src:anthropologist/academy] These were the model for the subsequent military academies throughout Europe, like the *Reale Accademia Militare* of Naples in 1787 and the Military Academy Karlberg in 1792.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The term is used widely today to refer to anything from schools to learned societies to funding agencies to private industry associations.
[src:anthropologist/academy] National academies are bodies for scientists, artists or writers that are usually state-funded and often are given the role of controlling much of the state funding for research into their areas, or other forms of funding.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Some use different terms in their name – the British Royal Society for example.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The membership typically comprises distinguished individuals in the relevant field, who may be elected by the other members, or appointed by the government.
[src:anthropologist/academy] They are essentially not schools or colleges, though some may operate teaching arms.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Académie Française was the most influential pattern for these.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Finland even has two separate "academies": Academy of Finland is a government-run funding agency, Suomalainen tiedeakatemia is a learned society.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, which presents the annual Academy Awards, is an example of a purely industry body using the name.
[src:anthropologist/academy] College-type specialized academies include the Royal Academy of Music of the United Kingdom; the United States Military Academy at West Point, New York; the United States Naval Academy; United States Air Force Academy; and the Australian Defence Force Academy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In emulation of the military academies, police in the United States are trained in police academies.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Because of the tradition of intellectual brilliance associated with this institution, many groups have chosen to use the word "academy" in their name, especially specialized tertiary educational institutions.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the early 19th century "academy" took the connotations that "gymnasium" was acquiring in German-speaking lands, of school that was less advanced than a college (for which it might prepare students) but considerably more than elementary.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Early American examples are the prestigious preparatory schools of Phillips Andover Academy, Phillips Exeter Academy and Deerfield Academy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In England, "academy" had a specialized meaning for schools, but the Edinburgh Academy was more like the American examples.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Academy was also used very loosely for various commercial training schools for dancing and the like.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Mozart organized public subscription performances of his music in Vienna in the 1780s and 1790s, he called the concerts "academies".
[src:anthropologist/academy] This usage in musical terms survives in the concert orchestra Academy of St Martin in the Fields and in the Brixton Academy, a concert hall in Brixton, South London.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Academies proliferated in the 20th century until even a three-week series of lectures and discussions would be termed an "academy".
[src:anthropologist/academy] In addition, the generic term "the academy" is sometimes used to refer to all of academia, which is sometimes considered a global successor to the academy of Athens.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In France, regional academic councils called academies are responsible for supervising all aspects of education in their region.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The academy regions are similar to, but not identical to, the standard French administrative regions.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The rector of each academy is a revocable nominee of the Ministry of Education.
[src:anthropologist/academy] These academies' main responsibility is overseeing primary and secondary education, but public universities are in some respects also answerable to the academy for their region.
[src:anthropologist/academy] However, French private universities are independent of the state and therefore independent of the regional academies.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In Imperial Russia and Soviet Union the term "academy", or Academy of Sciences was reserved to denote a state research establishment, see Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The latter one still exists in Russia, although other types of academies (study and honorary) appeared as well.
[src:anthropologist/academy] From the mid-seventeenth to the 19th centuries, educational institutions in England run by nonconformist groups that did not agree with the Church of England teachings were collectively known as "the dissenting academies".
[src:anthropologist/academy] As a place at an English public school or university generally required conformity to the Church of England, these institutions provided an alternative for those with different religious views and formed a significant part of England's educational system.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 2000, a form of "independent state schools", called "academies", were introduced in England.
[src:anthropologist/academy] They have been compared to US charter schools.
[src:anthropologist/academy] They are directly funded from central government rather than through local councils, and are partly privately sponsored.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Often the sponsors are from business, but some are sponsored by universities and charities.
[src:anthropologist/academy] These schools have greater autonomy than schools run by the local councils.
[src:anthropologist/academy] They are usually a type of secondary school, but some are "all through" schools with an integral primary school.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Some of the early ones were briefly known as "city academies"—the first such school opening on 10 September 2002 at the Business Academy Bexley.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Queen's Speech, which followed the 2010 general election, included proposals for a bill to allow the Secretary of State for Education to approve schools, both Primary and Secondary, that have been graded "outstanding" by Ofsted, to become academies.
[src:anthropologist/academy] This was to be through a simplified streamlined process not requiring sponsors to provide capital funding.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 2012, the UK government began forcing some schools which had been graded satisfactory or lower into becoming academies, unilaterally removing existing governing bodies and head teachers in some cases.
[src:anthropologist/academy] An example was Downhills Primary School in Haringey, where the head teacher refused to turn the school into an academy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] OFSTED were called in to assess the school, failed it, and both the head and the governing body were removed and replaced with a Government-appointed board despite opposition from the school and parents.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Prior to the twentieth century, education was not as carefully structured in the United States as it is in the twenty-first.
[src:anthropologist/academy] There was not a rigid division between high school and colleges.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The typical college at first included a preparatory unit, which it dropped by 1900.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the 1800s an academy was what later became known as a high school; in most places in the US there were no public schools above the primary level.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Some older high schools, such as Corning Free Academy, retained the term in their names (Corning Free Academy, later becoming a middle school, closed in 2014).
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1753, Benjamin Franklin established the academy and Charitable School of the Province of Pennsylvania.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1755, it was renamed the college and Academy and Charitable School of Philadelphia.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Today, it is known as the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The United States Military Academy was formed in 1802 as a college.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The academy movement in the US in the early 19th century arose from a public sense that education in the classic disciplines needed to be extended into the new territories and states that were being formed in the new western states.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Thousands of academies were started using local funds and tuition; most closed after a few years and others were established.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In 1860 there were 6,415 academies in operation.
[src:anthropologist/academy] When the Civil War erupted in 1861 they generally closed down temporarily; most in the South never reopened.
[src:anthropologist/academy] During the Age of Enlightenment in 18th-century Europe, the academy started to change in Europe.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the beginning of the 19th century Wilhelm von Humboldt not only published his philosophical paper *On the Limits of State Action*, but also directed the educational system in Prussia for a short time.
[src:anthropologist/academy] He introduced an academic system that was much more accessible to the lower classes.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Humboldt's Ideal was an education based on individuality, creativity, wholeness, and versatility.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Many continental European universities are still rooted in these ideas (or at least pay lip-service to them).
[src:anthropologist/academy] They are, however, in contradiction to today's massive trend of specialization in academia.
[src:anthropologist/academy] An **academic** is a person who works as a teacher or researcher at a university or other higher education institution.
[src:anthropologist/academy] An academic usually holds an advanced degree.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The term *scholar* is sometimes used with equivalent meaning to that of *academic* and describes in general those who attain mastery in a research discipline.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It has wider application, with it also being used to describe those whose occupation was research prior to organized higher education.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Academic administrators such as university presidents are not typically included in this use of the term *academic*, although many administrators hold advanced degrees and pursue scholarly research and writing while also tending to their administrative duties.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the United States, the term academic is approximately synonymous with that of the job title professor although in recent decades a growing number of institutions include librarians in the category of "academic staff".
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the United Kingdom, various titles of academic rank are used, typically research associate, research fellow (also senior research fellow and principal research fellow), lecturer (also senior lecturer and principal lecturer), reader, and professor.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The colloquial term don is sometimes substituted for teaching staff at Oxford and Cambridge.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Academia is usually conceived as divided into *disciplines* or *fields* of study.
[src:anthropologist/academy] These have their roots in the subjects of the medieval trivium and quadrivium, which provided the model for scholastic thought in the first universities in medieval Europe.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The disciplines have been much revised, and many new disciplines have become more specialized, researching smaller and smaller areas.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Because of this, *interdisciplinary* research is often prized in today's academy, though it can also be made difficult both by practical matters of administration and funding and by differing research methods of different disciplines.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In fact, many new fields of study have initially been conceived as interdisciplinary, and later become specialized disciplines in their own right – a recent example is cognitive science.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Most academic institutions reflect the divide of the disciplines in their administrative structure, being divided internally into *departments* or *programs* in various fields of study.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Each department is typically administered and funded separately by the academic institution, though there may be some overlap and faculty members, research and administrative staff may in some cases be shared among departments.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In addition, academic institutions generally have an overall administrative structure (usually including a president and several deans) which is controlled by no single department, discipline, or field of thought.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Also, the tenure system, a major component of academic employment and research in the US, serves to ensure that academia is relatively protected from political and financial pressures on thought.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The degree awarded for completed study is the primary academic qualification.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Typically these are, in order of completion, associate's degree, bachelor's degree (awarded for completion of undergraduate study), master's degree, and doctorate (awarded after graduate or postgraduate study).
[src:anthropologist/academy] These are only currently being standardized in Europe as part of the Bologna process, as many different degrees and standards of time to reach each are currently awarded in different countries in Europe.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In most fields the majority of academic researchers and teachers have doctorates or other terminal degrees, though in some professional and creative fields it is common for scholars and teachers to have only master's degrees.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Closely related to academic publishing is the practice of bringing a number of intellectuals in a field to give talks on their research at an academic conference, often allowing for a wider audience to be exposed to their ideas.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Nepotism is frequent in academia where it is frequent for professors to have their partners, and sometimes children, hired by the same faculty in which they work.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Universities are often culturally distinct from the towns or cities where they reside.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In some cases this leads to discomfort or outright conflict between local residents and members of the university over political, economic, or other issues.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Some localities in the Northeastern United States, for instance, have tried to block students from registering to vote as local residents—instead encouraging them to vote by absentee ballot at their primary residence—in order to retain control of local politics.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Other issues can include deep cultural and class divisions between local residents and university students.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The film *Breaking Away* dramatizes such a conflict.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Among the earliest research journals were the Proceedings of Meetings of the Royal Society in the 17th century.
[src:anthropologist/academy] At that time, the act of publishing academic inquiry was controversial, and widely ridiculed.
[src:anthropologist/academy] It was not at all unusual for a new discovery to be announced as an anagram, reserving priority for the discoverer, but indecipherable for anyone not in on the secret: both Isaac Newton and Leibniz used this approach.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Merton, a sociologist, found that 92 percent of cases of simultaneous discovery in the 17th century ended in dispute.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The number of disputes dropped to 72 percent in the 18th century, 59 percent by the latter half of the 19th century, and 33 percent by the first half of the 20th century.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The decline in contested claims for priority in research discoveries can be credited to the increasing acceptance of the publication of papers in modern academic journals.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The Royal Society was steadfast in its unpopular belief that science could only move forward through a transparent and open exchange of ideas backed by experimental evidence.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Many of the experiments were ones that we would not recognize as scientific today—nor were the questions they answered.
[src:anthropologist/academy] For example, when the Duke of Buckingham was admitted as a Fellow of the Royal Society on June 5, 1661, he presented the Society with a vial of powdered "unicorn horn".
[src:anthropologist/academy] It was a well-accepted 'fact' that a circle of unicorn's horn would act as an invisible cage for any spider.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Robert Hooke, the chief experimenter of the Royal Society, emptied the Duke's vial into a circle on a table and dropped a spider in the centre of the circle.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The spider promptly walked out of the circle and off the table.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In its day, this was cutting-edge research.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Research journals have been so successful that the number of journals and of papers has proliferated over the past few decades, and the credo of the modern academic has become "publish or perish".
[src:anthropologist/academy] Except for generalist journals such as *Science* or *Nature*, the topics covered in any single journal have tended to be narrow, and readership and citation have declined.
[src:anthropologist/academy] A variety of methods for reviewing submissions exist.
[src:anthropologist/academy] The most common involves initial approval by the journal, peer review by two or three researchers working in similar or closely related subjects who recommend approval or rejection as well as request error correction, clarification or additions before publishing.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Controversial topics may receive additional levels of review.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Journals have developed a hierarchy, partly based on reputation but also on the strictness of the review policy.
[src:anthropologist/academy] More prestigious journals are more likely to receive and publish more important work.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Submitters try to submit their work to the most prestigious journal likely to publish it to bolster their reputation and curriculum vitae.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Andrew Odlyzko, an academician with a large number of published research papers, has argued that research journals will evolve into something akin to Internet forums over the coming decade, by extending the interactivity of current Internet preprints.
[src:anthropologist/academy] This change may open them up to a wider range of ideas, some more developed than others.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Whether this will be a positive evolution remains to be seen.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Some claim that forums, like markets, tend to thrive or fail based on their ability to attract talent.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Some believe that highly restrictive and tightly monitored forums may be the least likely to thrive.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Gowns have been associated with academia since the birth of the university in the 14th and 15th centuries, perhaps because most early scholars were priests or church officials.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Over time, the gowns worn by degree-holders have become standardized to some extent, although traditions in individual countries and even institutions have established a diverse range of gown styles, and some have ended the custom entirely, even for graduation ceremonies.
[src:anthropologist/academy] At some universities, such as the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge, undergraduates may be required to wear gowns on formal occasions and on graduation.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Undergraduate gowns are usually a shortened version of a bachelor's gown.
[src:anthropologist/academy] At other universities, for example, outside the UK or US, the custom is entirely absent.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Students at the University of Trinity College at the University of Toronto wear gowns to formal dinner, debates, to student government, and to many other places.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In general, in the US and UK, recipients of a bachelor's degree are entitled to wear a simple full-length robe without adornment and a mortarboard cap with a tassel.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In addition, holders of a bachelor's degree may be entitled to wear a ceremonial hood at some schools.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the US, bachelor's hoods are rarely seen.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Bachelor's hoods are generally smaller versions of those worn by recipients of master's and doctoral degrees.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Recipients of a master's degree in the US or UK wear a similar cap and gown but closed sleeves with slits, and usually receive a ceremonial hood that hangs down the back of the gown.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the US the hood is traditionally edged with a silk or velvet strip displaying the disciplinary color, and is lined with the university's colors.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Recipients of a doctoral degree tend to have the most elaborate academic dress, and hence there is the greatest diversity at this level.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the US, doctoral gowns are similar to the gowns worn by master's graduates, with the addition of velvet stripes across the sleeves and running down the front of the gown which may be tinted with the disciplinary color for the degree received.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Holders of a doctoral degree may be entitled or obliged to wear *scarlet* (a special gown in scarlet) on high days and special occasions.
[src:anthropologist/academy] While some doctoral graduates wear the mortarboard cap traditional to the lower degree levels, most wear a cap or *Tudor bonnet* that resembles a tam o'shanter, from which a colored tassel is suspended.
[src:anthropologist/academy] In modern times, in the US and UK, gowns are normally only worn at graduation ceremonies, although some colleges still demand the wearing of academic dress on formal occasions (official banquets and other similar affairs).
[src:anthropologist/academy] In the 19th and early 20th centuries, it was more common to see the dress worn in the classroom, a practice which has now all but disappeared.
[src:anthropologist/academy] Two notable exceptions are Oxford and a society at Sewanee, where students are required to wear formal academic dress in the examination room.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In humans, ageing represents the accumulation of changes in a human being over time and can encompass physical, psychological, and social changes.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Reaction time, for example, may slow with age, while memories and general knowledge typically increase.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Of the roughly 150,000 people who die each day across the globe, about two-thirds die from age-related causes.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Programmed ageing should not be confused with programmed cell death (apoptosis).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Human beings and members of other species, especially animals, age and die.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In contrast, many species can be considered potentially immortal: for example, bacteria fission to produce daughter cells, strawberry plants grow runners to produce clones of themselves, and animals in the genus *Hydra* have a regenerative ability by which they avoid dying of old age.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Early life forms on Earth, starting at least 3.7 billion years ago, were single-celled organisms.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Such organisms (Prokaryotes, Protozoans, algae) multiply by fission into daughter cells; thus single celled organisms have been thought to not age and to be potentially immortal under favorable conditions.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] However, evidence has been reported that aging leading to death occurs in the single-cell bacterium *Escherichia coli*, an organism that reproduces by morphologically symmetrical division.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Evidence of aging has also been reported for the bacterium *Caulobacter crescintus*. and the single cell yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Ageing and mortality of the individual organism became more evident with the evolution of eukaryotic sexual reproduction, which occurred with the emergence of the fungal/animal kingdoms approximately a billion years ago, and the evolution of seed-producing plants 320 million years ago.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The sexual organism could henceforth pass on some of its genetic material to produce new individuals and could itself become disposable with respect to the survival of its species.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This classic biological idea has however been perturbed recently by the discovery that the bacterium *E. coli* may split into distinguishable daughter cells, which opens the theoretical possibility of "age classes" among bacteria.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Even within humans and other mortal species, there are cells with the potential for immortality: cancer cells which have lost the ability to die when maintained in a cell culture such as the HeLa cell line, and specific stem cells such as germ cells (producing ova and spermatozoa).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In artificial cloning, adult cells can be rejuvenated to embryonic status and then used to grow a new tissue or animal without ageing.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Normal human cells however die after about 50 cell divisions in laboratory culture (the Hayflick limit, discovered by Leonard Hayflick in 1961).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A number of characteristic signs and symptoms of ageing are experienced by a majority, or by a significant proportion of humans during their lifetimes.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] These age-related changes can vary in different bodily systems and among individuals, a heterogeneity referred to as 'mosaic ageing'.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] About 3% of people between the ages of 65 and 74, 19% of those between 75 and 84, and nearly half of those over 85 years old have dementia.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The spectrum ranges from mild cognitive impairment to the neurodegenerative diseases of Alzheimer's disease, cerebrovascular disease, Parkinson's disease and Lou Gehrig's disease.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Furthermore, many types of memory decline with ageing, but not semantic memory or general knowledge such as vocabulary definitions.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] These typically increase or remain steady until late adulthood .
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Intelligence declines with age, though the rate varies depending on the type and may, in fact, remain steady throughout most of the human lifespan, dropping suddenly only as people near the end of their lives.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Individual variations in the rate of cognitive decline may therefore be explained in terms of people having different lengths of life.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] There are changes to the brain: after 20 years of age, there is a 10% reduction each decade in the total length of the brain's myelinated axons.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Age can result in visual impairment, whereby non-verbal communication is reduced, which can lead to isolation and possible depression.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Older adults, however, may not experience depression as much as younger adults, and were paradoxically found to have improved mood, despite declining physical health.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Macular degeneration causes vision loss and increases with age, affecting nearly 12% of those above the age of 80.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This degeneration is caused by systemic changes in the circulation of waste products and by the growth of abnormal vessels around the retina.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Other visual diseases that often appear with age are cataracts and glaucoma.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A cataract occurs when the lens of the eye becomes cloudy, making vision blurry; it eventually causes blindness if untreated.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] They develop over time and are seen most often with those that are older.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Cataracts can be treated through surgery.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Glaucoma is another common visual disease that appears in older adults.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Glaucoma is caused by damage to the optic nerve, causing vision loss.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Glaucoma usually develops over time, but there are variations to glaucoma, and some have a sudden onset.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] There are a few procedures for glaucoma, but there is no cure or fix for the damage, once it has occurred.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Prevention is the best measure in the case of glaucoma.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A distinction can be made between "proximal ageing" (age-based effects that come about because of factors in the recent past) and "distal ageing" (age-based differences that can be traced to a cause in a person's early life, such as childhood poliomyelitis).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Ageing is among the greatest known risk factors for most human diseases.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Of the roughly 150,000 people who die each day across the globe, about two-thirds — 100,000 per day — die from age-related causes.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In industrialized nations, the proportion is higher, reaching 90%.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In the 21st century, researchers are only beginning to investigate the biological basis of ageing even in relatively simple and short-lived organisms, such as yeast.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Little is known of mammalian ageing, in part due to the much longer lives of even small mammals, such as the mouse (around 3 years).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A model organism for the study of ageing is the nematode *C. elegans* – having a short lifespan of 2–3 weeks – enabling genetic manipulations or suppression of gene activity with RNA interference, and other factors.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Most known mutations and RNA interference targets that extend lifespan were first discovered in *C. elegans*.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The factors proposed to influence biological ageing fall into two main categories, *programmed* and *error-related*.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Programmed factors follow a biological timetable that might be a continuation of inherent mechanisms that regulate childhood growth and development.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This regulation would depend on changes in gene expression that affect the systems responsible for maintenance, repair and defense responses.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Factors causing errors or damage include internal and environmental events that induce cumulative deterioration in one or more organs.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The rate of ageing varies substantially across different species, and this, to a large extent, is genetically based.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] For example, numerous perennial plants ranging from strawberries and potatoes to willow trees typically produce clones of themselves by vegetative reproduction and are thus potentially immortal, while annual plants such as wheat and watermelons die each year and reproduce by sexual reproduction.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In 2008 it was discovered that inactivation of only two genes in the annual plant *Arabidopsis thaliana* leads to its conversion into a potentially immortal perennial plant.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The oldest animals known so far are 15,000-year-old Antarctic sponges, which can reproduce both sexually and clonally.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Such organisms are sometimes said to exhibit negligible senescence.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The genetic aspect has also been demonstrated in studies of human centenarians.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A 2025 study published in *Cell* examined protein changes in 516 tissue samples collected from 76 human donors ranging in age from 14 to 68.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Researchers developed tissue-specific "proteomic clocks" to trace how ageing progresses across different organs.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Their analysis revealed a noticeable shift in the rate of ageing around age 50, with the steepest changes occurring between ages 45 and 55—particularly in blood vessels.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Among the various tissues studied, the aorta showed the most significant changes in protein makeup.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] One of the proteins identified, GAS6, was linked to faster ageing; when introduced into mice, it triggered early vascular deterioration and other signs of systemic ageing.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The research also found that some organs, like the adrenal gland, begin showing ageing-related changes as early as age 30, suggesting that not all parts of the body age at the same pace.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The findings suggest that human ageing accelerates midlife rather than progressing steadily throughout adulthood.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Life span, like other phenotypes, is selected for in evolution.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Traits that benefit early survival and reproduction will be selected for even if they contribute to an earlier death.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The biological mechanisms which regulate lifespan probably evolved with the first multicellular organisms more than a billion years ago.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] However, even single-celled organisms such as yeast have been used as models in ageing; hence, ageing has its biological roots much earlier than multi-cellularity.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The Mediterranean diet is credited with lowering the risk of heart disease and early death.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The major contributors to mortality risk reduction appear to be a higher consumption of vegetables, fish, fruits, nuts and monounsaturated fatty acids, such as by consuming olive oil.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] As of 2021, there is insufficient clinical evidence that calorie restriction or any dietary practice affects the process of ageing.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] People who participate in moderate to high levels of physical exercise have a lower mortality rate compared to individuals who are not physically active.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The majority of the benefits from exercise are achieved with around 3500 metabolic equivalent (MET) minutes per week.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] For example, climbing stairs 10 minutes, vacuuming 15 minutes, gardening 20 minutes, running 20 minutes, and walking or bicycling for 25 minutes on a daily basis would *together* achieve about 3000 MET minutes a week.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Exercise has also been found to be an effective measure to treat declines in neuromuscular function due to age.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A meta-analysis found that resistance training with elastic bands or kettlebells provided significant improvements to grip strength, gait speed, and skeletal muscle mass in patients with sarcopenia.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Furthermore, another analysis found that the positive effects of resistance exercise on strength, muscle mass, and motor coordination reduce the risk of falls in the elderly, which is a key factor for living a longer and healthier life.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In terms of programming, there is no one-size-fits-all approach.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] There is also evidence to suggest that exercise of any type may mitigate the degradation of the neuromuscular junction (NMJ) that occurs with age.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Current evidence suggests that aerobic exercise causes the most hypertrophy of the NMJ, although resistance training is still somewhat effective.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] However, further evidence is necessary to identify optimal training protocols for NMJ function and to further understand how exercise affects the mechanisms that cause NMJ degradation.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A meta-analysis showed that loneliness carries a higher mortality risk than smoking.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Different cultures express age in different ways.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The age of an adult human is commonly measured in whole years since the day of birth.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Informal terms include "tweens", "teenagers", "twentysomething", "thirtysomething", etc. as well as "denarian", "vicenarian", "tricenarian", "quadragenarian", etc.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Most legal systems define a specific age for when an individual is allowed or obliged to do particular activities.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] These age specifications include voting age, drinking age, age of consent, age of majority, age of criminal responsibility, marriageable age, age of candidacy, and mandatory retirement age.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Admission to a movie, for instance, may depend on age according to a motion picture rating system.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A bus fare might be discounted for the young or old.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Each nation, government, and non-governmental organization has different ways of classifying age.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In other words, chronological ageing may be distinguished from "social ageing" (cultural age-expectations of how people should act as they grow older) and "biological ageing" (an organism's physical state as it ages).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Ageism cost the United States $63 billion in one year according to a Yale School of Public Health study.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In a UNFPA report about ageing in the 21st century, it highlighted the need to "Develop a new rights-based culture of ageing and a change of mindset and societal attitudes towards ageing and older persons, from welfare recipients to active, contributing members of society".
[src:anthropologist/ageing] UNFPA said that this "requires, among others, working towards the development of international human rights instruments and their translation into national laws and regulations and affirmative measures that challenge age discrimination and recognise older people as autonomous subjects".
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Older people's music participation contributes to the maintenance of interpersonal relationships and promoting successful ageing.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] At the same time, older persons can make contributions to society including caregiving and volunteering.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] For example, "A study of Bolivian migrants who [had] moved to Spain found that 69% left their children at home, usually with grandparents.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Population ageing is the increase in the number and proportion of older people in society.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Population ageing has three possible causes: migration, longer life expectancy (decreased death rate) and decreased birth rate.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Ageing has a significant impact on society.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Young people tend to have fewer legal privileges (if they are below the age of majority), they are more likely to push for political and social change, to develop and adopt new technologies, and to need education.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Older people have different requirements from society and government, and frequently have differing values as well, such as for property and pension rights.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In the 21st century, one of the most significant population trends is ageing.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Currently, over 11% of the world's current population are people aged 60 and older and the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) estimates that by 2050 that number will rise to approximately 22%.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Ageing has occurred due to development which has enabled better nutrition, sanitation, health care, education and economic well-being.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Consequently, fertility rates have continued to decline and life expectancy has risen.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Life expectancy at birth is over 80 now in 33 countries.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] As life expectancy rises and birth rates decline in developed countries, the median age rises accordingly.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] According to the United Nations, this process is taking place in nearly every country in the world.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A rising median age can have significant social and economic implications, as the workforce gets progressively older and the number of old workers and retirees grows relative to the number of young workers.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Older people generally incur more health-related costs than do younger people in the workplace and can also cost more in worker's compensation and pension liabilities.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In most developed countries an older workforce is somewhat inevitable.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In the United States for instance, the Bureau of Labor Statistics estimates that one in four American workers will be 55 or older by 2020.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Among the most urgent concerns of older persons worldwide is income security.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This poses challenges for governments with ageing populations to ensure investments in pension systems continues to provide economic independence and reduce poverty in old age.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] These challenges vary for developing and developed countries.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The global economic crisis has increased financial pressure to ensure economic security and access to health care in old age.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] It has been argued that population ageing has undermined economic development and can lead to lower inflation because elderly individuals care especially strongly about the value of their pensions and savings.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Evidence suggests that pensions, while making a difference to the well-being of older persons, also benefit entire families especially in times of crisis when there may be a shortage or loss of employment within households.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A study by the Australian Government in 2003 estimated that "women between the ages of 65 and 74 years contribute A$16 billion per year in unpaid caregiving and voluntary work.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Due to increasing share of the elderly in the population, health care expenditures will continue to grow relative to the economy in coming decades.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This has been considered as a negative phenomenon and effective strategies like labour productivity enhancement should be considered to deal with negative consequences of ageing.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In the field of sociology and mental health, ageing is seen in five different views: ageing as maturity, ageing as decline, ageing as a life-cycle event, ageing as generation, and ageing as survival.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Positive correlates with ageing often include economics, employment, marriage, children, education, and sense of control, as well as many others.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The social science of ageing includes disengagement theory, activity theory, selectivity theory, and continuity theory.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Retirement, a common transition faced by the elderly, may have both positive and negative consequences.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] As cyborgs currently are on the rise some theorists argue there is a need to develop new definitions of ageing and for instance a bio-techno-social definition of ageing has been suggested.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] There is a current debate as to whether or not the pursuit of longevity and the postponement of senescence are cost-effective health care goals given finite health care resources.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Because of the accumulated infirmities of old age, bioethicist Ezekiel Emanuel, opines that the pursuit of longevity via the compression of morbidity hypothesis is a "fantasy" and that human life is not worth living after age 75; longevity then should not be a goal of health care policy.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This opinion has been contested by neurosurgeon and medical ethicist Miguel Faria, who states that life can be worthwhile during old age, and that longevity should be pursued in association with the attainment of quality of life.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Faria claims that postponement of senescence as well as happiness and wisdom can be attained in old age in a large proportion of those who lead healthy lifestyles and remain intellectually active.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] With age inevitable biological changes occur that increase the risk of illness and disability.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] "A life-cycle approach to health care – one that starts early, continues through the reproductive years and lasts into old age – is essential for the physical and emotional well-being of older persons, and, indeed, all people.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Many societies in Western Europe and Japan have ageing populations.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] While the effects on society are complex, there is a concern about the impact on health care demand.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] However, the annual growth in national health spending is not mainly due to increasing demand from ageing populations, but rather has been driven by rising incomes, costly new medical technology, a shortage of health care workers and informational asymmetries between providers and patients.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A number of health problems become more prevalent as people get older.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] These include mental health problems as well as physical health problems, especially dementia.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] It has been estimated that population ageing only explains 0.2 percentage points of the annual growth rate in medical spending of 4.3% since 1970.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In addition, certain reforms to the Medicare system in the United States decreased elderly spending on home health care by 12.5% per year between 1996 and 2000.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The increase in demand for cosmeceuticals has led scientists to find ingredients for these products in unorthodox places.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] For example, the secretion of cryptomphalus aspersa (or brown garden snail) has been found to have antioxidant properties, increase skin cell proliferation, and increase extracellular proteins such as collagen and fibronectin (important proteins for cell proliferation).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Another substance used to prevent the physical manifestations of ageing is onobotulinumtoxinA, the toxin injected for Botox.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In some cultures, old age is celebrated and honoured.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In Korea, for example, a special party called hwangap is held to celebrate and congratulate an individual for turning 60 years old.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In China, respect for elderly is often the basis for how a community is organized and has been at the foundation of Chinese culture and morality for thousands of years.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Older people are respected for their wisdom and most important decisions have traditionally not been made without consulting them.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This is a similar case for most Asian countries such as the Philippines, Thailand, Vietnam, Singapore, etc.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Positive self-perceptions of ageing are associated with better mental and physical health and well-being.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Positive self-perception of health has been correlated with higher well-being and reduced mortality among the elderly.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This finding is generally stronger for men than women, though this relationship is not universal across all studies and may only be true in some circumstances.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] As people age, subjective health remains relatively stable, even though objective health worsens.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In fact, perceived health improves with age when objective health is controlled in the equation.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This phenomenon is known as the "paradox of ageing".
[src:anthropologist/ageing] This may be a result of social comparison; for instance, the older people get, the more they may consider themselves in better health than their same-aged peers.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Elderly people often associate their functional and physical decline with the normal ageing process.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] One way to help younger people experience what it feels like to be older is through an ageing suit.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] There are several different kinds of suits including the GERT (named as a reference to gerontology), the R70i exoskeleton, and the AGNES (Age Gain Now Empathy Suit) suits.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] These suits create the feelings of the effects of ageing by adding extra weight and increased pressure in certain points like the wrists, ankles and other joints.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In addition, the various suits have different ways to impair vision and hearing to simulate the loss of these senses.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] To create the loss of feeling in hands that the elderly experience, special gloves are a part of the uniforms.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Use of these suits may help to increase the amount of empathy felt for the elderly and could be considered particularly useful for those who are either learning about ageing, or those who work with the elderly, such as nurses or care centre staff.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Design is another field that could benefit from the empathy these suits may cause.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] When designers understand what it feels like to have the impairments of old age, they can better design buildings, packaging, or even tools to help with the simple day-to-day tasks that are more difficult with less dexterity.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Designing with the elderly in mind may help to reduce the negative feelings that are associated with the loss of abilities that the elderly face.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The healthy ageing framework, proposed by the World Health Organization operationalizes health as functional ability, which results from the interactions of intrinsic capacity and the environments.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Intrinsic capacity is a construct encompassing people's physical and mental abilities which can be drawn upon during ageing.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Intrinsic capacity comprises the domains of: cognition, locomotion, vitality/nutrition, psychological and sensory (visual and hearing).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A recent study found four "profiles" or "statuses" of intrinsic capacity among older adults, namely high IC (43% at baseline), low deterioration with impaired locomotion (17%), high deterioration without cognitive impairment (22%) and high deterioration with cognitive impairment (18%).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Over half of the study sample remained in the same status at baseline and follow-up (61%).
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Around one-fourth of participants transitioned from the high IC to the low deterioration status, and only 3% of the participants improved their status.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Interestingly, the probability of improvement was observed in the status of high deterioration.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Participants in the latent statuses of low and high levels of deterioration had a significantly higher risk of frailty, disability and dementia than their high IC counterparts.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] A superager (also super-ager) is a person of advanced biological age (80 years or older) who retains the cognitive performance of a much younger person.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The term was coined by the neurologist Marsel Mesulam.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Individuals of this range of age who show normal performance are called "typical-agers" to differentiate them from superagers.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The concept of *successful ageing* can be traced back to the 1950s and was popularized in the 1980s.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Traditional definitions of successful ageing have emphasized absence of physical and cognitive disabilities.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] In their 1987 article, Rowe and Kahn characterized successful ageing as involving three components: a) freedom from disease and disability, b) high cognitive and physical functioning, and c) social and productive engagement.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] The study cited previous was also done back in 1987 and therefore, these factors associated with successful ageing have probably been changed.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] With the current knowledge, scientists started to focus on learning about the effect of spirituality in successful ageing.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] There are some differences in cultures as to which of these components are the most important.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Most often across cultures, social engagement was the most highly rated but depending on the culture the definition of successful ageing changes.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Education is considered an important factor in living a long, healthy, and fulfilling life.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Research shows that people who spend more years in school often live longer, enjoy better health, and maintain sharper cognitive abilities as they age.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Education provides access to more resources, encourages healthy habits, and helps individuals make informed decisions about diet, exercise, and medical care, all of which contribute to improved well-being in later life.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] Cognitive scientists also suggest that education strengthens the mind.
[src:anthropologist/ageing] While some abilities, such as solving unfamiliar problems, may decline with age, other skills—like applying accumulated knowledge and experience—can remain stable or even improve.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Alfred Reginald Radcliffe-Brown was born Alfred Reginald Brown in Sparkbrook, Birmingham, England, the second son of Alfred Brown (d.1886), a manufacturer's clerk, and Hannah Brown (née Radcliffe).
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] He later changed his surname, by deed poll, to Radcliffe-Brown, Radcliffe being his mother's maiden name.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] He was educated at King Edward's School, Birmingham, and Trinity College, Cambridge (B.A., 1905; M.A., 1909), graduating with first-class honours in the moral sciences tripos.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] At Trinity College, he was elected Anthony Wilkin student in 1906 and 1909.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] While still a student, he earned the nickname "Anarchy Brown" for his close interest in the writings of the anarcho-communist and scientist Peter Kropotkin.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Rivers who, with Alfred Cort Haddon, guided him toward social anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] With the latter's influence, he travelled to the Andaman Islands (1906–1908) and Western Australia (1910–1912, with biologist and writer E.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Grant Watson and Australian writer Daisy Bates) to perform fieldwork concerning the workings of the societies there.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] His time in the Andaman Islands and Western Australia were the basis of his later books *The Andaman Islanders* (1922) and *The Social Organization of Australian Tribes* (1930).
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] At the 1914 meeting of the British Association for the Advancement of Science, in Melbourne, Bates accused him of plagiarising her work, based on an unpublished manuscript she had sent him for comment.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Before departing for Western Australia, Brown married Winifred Marie Lyon in Cambridge; they had one daughter, Mary Cynthia Lyon Radcliffe.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] The couple became estranged by about 1926.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] They may have divorced in 1938 (sources disagree on whether a divorce was completed).
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] In 1916 Brown became a director of education in Tonga.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] In 1921 he relocated to Cape Town to become professor of social anthropology, initiating the School of African Life.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Further university appointments were University of Cape Town (1921–1925), University of Sydney (1925–1931) and University of Chicago (1931–1937).
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Among his most prominent students during his years at the University of Chicago were Sol Tax and Fred Eggan.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] While at the University of Sydney, he was a cultivator of the arts, and championed Edward de Vere, 17th Earl of Oxford as the author of the works attributed to Shakespeare.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Fearing that the Depression would result in financial collapse, Radcliffe-Brown departed in 1931 for a professorship with the University of Chicago, leaving his successors to solicit Rockefeller grants and government funds to save the Sydney Department.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] After these various far-flung appointments, he returned to England in 1937 to begin an appointment to the first chair in social anthropology at Oxford University in 1937.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] He had this post until his retirement in 1946.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Survived by his daughter, he died in London in 1955 at the age of 74.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] While Radcliffe-Brown founded the Institute of Social and Cultural Anthropology at Oxford, according to Rodney Needham his absence from the institute during the war years prevented his theories and method from having a major influence on Oxford anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown was influenced by his tutor, W.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Rouse Ball, to study a moral science (psychology, philosophical subjects, and economics) instead of a natural science which he originally wanted to choose.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] During his time at Cambridge, professors Haddon and Rivers encouraged him to study anthropology and discover his interests in the topic.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Haddon guided him towards the comparative method in specific societies in anthropology, classification and morphology, inductive generalization, and to sympathize with Durkheim's methods.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] He has been described as "the classic to Bronisław Malinowski's romantic".
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown brought French sociology (namely Émile Durkheim) to British anthropology, constructing a rigorous battery of concepts to frame ethnography.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Durkheim inspired Radcliffe-Brown throughout the entirety of his profession in anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] One of Radcliffe-Brown's goals was to "transform anthropology into a 'real' science based on the natural sciences".
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] He demonstrated these ideologies in his book published in 1957, *A Natural Science of Society*.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] In 1906, one of Alfred's primary studies concerned the kinship and familial relations of Western Australians.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Within these communities, he discerned distinct social organizations that proved that adaptation and fusion were essential in keeping the system functioning.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] The term "Structural Functionalism" would later be used to describe the idea that "the life of a society may be viewed as an active system of functionally consistent, interdependent elements".
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown has often been associated with functionalism, and is considered by some to be the founder of structural functionalism.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Structural Functionalism, which can be traced back to sociologist Émile Durkheim, is the social theory that assumes societal institution (e.g.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Government, school systems, family structures, etc.) play a role in its success.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Alfred developed these principles believing that studying social structures like kinship ties would be evidence enough for understanding how social structures affect the maintenance of a society, stating, "human beings are connected by a complex network of social relations.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] I use the term "social structure" to denote this network of actually existing relations".
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] (On Social Structure, 190) He also clarifies that "We may define it as a condition in which all parts of the system work together with a sufficient degree of harmony or internal consistency, i.e., without producing persistent conflicts which can neither be resolved nor regulated".
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] (On the Concept of Function in Social Science, 181).
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Nonetheless, Radcliffe-Brown vehemently denied being a functionalist, and carefully distinguished his concept of function from that of Malinowski, who openly advocated functionalism.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] While Malinowski's functionalism claimed that social practices could be explained directly by their ability to satisfy basic biological needs, Radcliffe-Brown rejected this as baseless.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Instead, influenced by the process philosophy of Alfred North Whitehead, he claimed that the fundamental units of anthropology were processes of human life and interaction.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Because these are by definition characterized by constant flux, what needs explaining is the occurrence of stability.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Why Radcliffe-Brown asked, would some patterns of social practices repeat themselves and even seem to become fixed?
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] He reasoned that this would at least require that other practices must not conflict with them too much; and that in some cases, it may be that practices grow to reinforce each other, a notion he termed 'coadaptation', deriving from the biological term.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Functional analysis, then, was just the attempt to explain stability by discovering how practices fit together to sustain that stability; the 'function' of practice was just its role in sustaining the overall social structure, insofar as there was a stable social structure (Radcliffe-Brown 1957).
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] In addition to identifying abstract relationships between social structures, Radcliffe-Brown argued for the importance of the notion of a 'total social structure', which is the sum total of social relations in a given social unit of analysis during a given period.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] The identification of 'functions' of social practices was supposed to be relative to this total social structure.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Lévi-Strauss considered social structure as a model.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown's research emphasized simple, non-literate societies.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] He believed kinship played a large role in these societies, and that patrilineages, clans, tribes and units all relate to kinship rules in society and are essential in political organization.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown claimed that all research on social structure is based on observations, what anthropologists see and hear about individual peoples.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown also argued that the study of social structure encompassed culture, therefore there is no need for a separate topic dedicated to culture.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] A major opinion concerning tribal societies had been that all societies follow a unilineal cultural sequence ('evolutionism'), and that therefore 'primitive' societies could be understood as earlier stages of that sequence; conversely, 'modern' societies contained vestiges of older forms.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Another opinion was that social practices tend to develop only once, and that therefore commonalities and differences between societies could be explained by a historical reconstruction of the interaction between societies ('diffusionism').
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] According to both of these opinions, the proper way to explain differences between tribal societies and modern ones was historical reconstruction.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown rejected both of these opinions because of the untestable nature of historical reconstructions.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Instead, he argued for the use of the comparative method to find regularities in human societies and thereby build a genuinely scientific knowledge of social life.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] To that end, Radcliffe-Brown argued for a 'natural science of society'.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] He claimed that there was an independent role for social anthropology in that respect, separate from psychology, though not in conflict with it.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] This was because psychology was to be the study of individual mental processes, while social anthropology was to study processes of interaction between people (social relations).
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Thus he argued for a principled ontological distinction between psychology and social anthropology, in the same way as one might try to make a principled distinction between physics and biology.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Moreover, he claimed that existing social scientific disciplines, with the possible exception of linguistics, were arbitrary; once our knowledge of society is sufficient, he argued, we will be able to form subdisciplines of anthropology concerning relatively isolated parts of the social structure.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] But without extensive scientific knowledge, it is impossible to know where the boundaries should be defined.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown was often criticised for failing to consider the effect of historical changes in the societies he studied, in particular changes brought about by colonialism.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Nevertheless, he is now considered, along with Bronisław Malinowski, as one of the founders of modern social anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Radcliffe-Brown performed extensive fieldwork in the Andaman Islands, Australia, and elsewhere.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] On the basis of this research, he contributed extensively to the anthropological ideas concerning kinship, and criticised Lévi-Strauss's Alliance theory.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] He also produced structural analyses of myths, including on the basis of the concept of binary distinctions and dialectical opposition, an idea later echoed by Lévi-Strauss.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] According to Radcliffe-Brown, the function of religion is to install a sense of dependence on fear and other emotional strain on the human body into a society.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] Therefore, a major function of religion is to affirm and strengthen sentiments necessary for a society to continue.
[src:anthropologist/alfred-radcliffe-brown] This idea was developed in Radcliffe-Browns book, *The Andaman Islanders* (Free Press 1963).
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The **American Anthropological Association** (**AAA**) is an American organization of scholars and practitioners in the field of anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The AAA publishes more than 20 peer-reviewed scholarly journals, available in print and online through AnthroSource.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The first anthropological society in the US was the American Ethnological Society of New York, which was founded by Albert Gallatin and revived in 1899 by Franz Boas after a hiatus.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] 1879 saw the establishment of the Anthropological Society of Washington (which first published the journal *American Anthropologist*, before it became a national journal), and 1882 saw the American Association for the Advancement of Science established an anthropological section.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Boas and other anthropologist discussed the possibility of creating a single national society already in 1898, but fears that it might damage the AAAS caused a long discussion.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] In 1901 the AES and ASW sent members to attend the meeting of the AAAS anthropologists in Chicago in which discussions continued and there was general agreement that a national society should be formed.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Boas advocated a restricted membership of 40 "professional anthropologists", but the AAA's first president, W.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] McGee, ensured that membership would be open to everyone with an interest in the discipline.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] At its incorporation, it assumed responsibility for the journal*American Anthropologist*, created in 1888 by the Anthropological Society of Washington (ASW).
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Business affairs are conducted by a 41-member Section Assembly representing each of the association's constituent sections, and a 15-member Executive Board.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] From an initial membership of 175, the AAA grew slowly during the first half of the 20th century.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Annual meetings were held primarily in the Northeast and accommodated all attendees in a single room.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The offices of the AAA are located in Arlington, Virginia.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The AAA is composed of 40 sections, which are groups organized around identity affiliations or intellectual interests within the discipline of anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Sections each have an elected president or chair; many publish journals and host meetings.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The AAA publishes more than 20 section publications including *American Anthropologist*, *American Ethnologist*, *Cultural Anthropology*, *Anthropology & Education Quarterly* and *Medical Anthropology Quarterly*.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The AAA's official magazine, *Anthropology News*, is published bimonthly.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] AAA publications are available online through AnthroSource.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Since 2007, journals have been published in partnership with Wiley-Blackwell since 2007.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Since 1962 the association has published the AAA AnthroGuide, giving staff and program information about anthropology departments.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Other issues addressed from the 1970s through the 1980s included illegal antiquities trade, the insertion of religious beliefs into social science texts, the preservation of endangered nonhuman primates, and the religious significance of peyote to Native Americans.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] In 2004, in response to President George W.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Bush's call for a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage, the Association issued a statement on marriage and the family.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The Association also has adopted resolutions against the 2003 invasion of Iraq, against the use of anthropological knowledge as an element for physical or psychological torture, and against any covert or overt U.S. military action against Iran.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Following a referendum in 2023, the Association endorsed a boycott of Israeli academic institutions, joining the BDS movement.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] A number of ideologically polarized debates within the discipline of anthropology have prompted the association to conduct investigations.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] These include the dispute between Derek Freeman and defenders of Margaret Mead, as well as the controversy over the book *Darkness in El Dorado*.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The AAA has issued a number of statements on the topic of race, and since the 1950s has argued publicly that race is best understood as a cultural or bio-cultural rather than mostly biological construction.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] In 2006, the association developed and continues to manage a public education program titled "RACE: Are We So Different?" The program includes a traveling museum exhibit, an interactive website, and educational materials.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Initially, AAA was highly skeptical of the concept of universal human rights, with some anthropologists arguing that because of cultural relativism there are no principles that can be universally valid for humans of all cultures.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] IN 1947 the AAA issued a statement on Human rights, noting that value judgments are culturally contextual and arguing that a declaration about universal human rights ought to take into consideration and encompass all the different human value systems.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] This stance has gradually been abandoned by most anthropologists, many of whom today see universal human rights as an important way through which discrimination and oppression of cultural minorities can be reduced.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] District Court in Arizona entered a permanent injunction barring enforcement of the remaining provisions.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] With the law's repeal, AAA's ban on considering AAA conferences in Arizona was lifted.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Through 2007 and 2008, debates surrounding anthropologists and the military resurfaced in response to the Pentagon's Human Terrain System (HTS) project.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Following a number of national news articles on the project, anthropologists began to debate the project and related ethical issues.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Proponents of the program argued that anthropologists were providing much-needed cultural knowledge about local populations and helping to decrease violence in their areas of operation.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Critics, however, argued that HTS anthropologists could not receive informed consent from their research subjects in a war zone and that information provided by anthropologists might put populations in danger.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] To address these issues, the Association's Executive Board released a statement on 31 October 2007.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] It cited "sufficiently troubling and urgent ethical issues" raised by the project, including the difficulties for HTS anthropologists to receive informed consent without coercion from their research subjects and to uphold their ethical mandate to "do no harm" to those they study.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] The AAA urged members to adhere to its code of ethics, which outlines principles and guidelines for ethical behavior.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] However, the association does not adjudicate cases involving charges of unethical behavior or bar members from participating in the HTS program.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] In addition, the Association's Commission on the Engagement of Anthropology with US Security and Intelligence Communities (CEAUSSIC) issued a final report released during the AAA's 2007 annual meeting, based on over a year of work.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] It neither endorsed nor condemned anthropological work with military, intelligence and security organizations, but instead outlined the opportunities and challenges of working in these sectors.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Opposition to military cooperation was evident during that meeting.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Some critics of the HTS program have suggested that scholars who perform classified work with the military be expelled from the organization.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] During an event organized by the Network of Concerned Anthropologists, a graduate student who had recently been expelled from the HTS program spoke out about her experiences.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] She argued that the program was poorly run but was doing positive work in helping military officers with "nation-building" activities.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Until August 2007, AnthroSource was a collaboration between the University of California Press and the Association.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] It, along with all their journals, has since been removed from the University of California Press by the AAA Board and transferred to Wiley-Blackwell.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] Commencing 2008, AnthroSource was to be hosted and managed by Wiley-Blackwell as part of the five-year publishing contract awarded.
[src:anthropologist/american-anthropological-association] AAA presidents have been drawn from all of the four subdisciplines of American anthropology: Until 2003 the presidents counted 46 socio-cultural anthropologists, 19 archeologists, six physical anthropologists and six linguists.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] In genealogy and evolutionary biology, an **ancestor**, also known as a **forefather**, **fore-elder**, or a **forebear**, is a parent or (recursively) the parent of an antecedent (i.e., a grandparent, great-grandparent, great-great-grandparent and so forth).
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] *Ancestor* is "any person from whom one is descended.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] Two individuals have a genetic relationship if one is the ancestor of the other or if they share a common ancestor.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] In evolutionary theory, species which share an evolutionary ancestor are said to be of common descent.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] However, this concept of ancestry does not apply to some bacteria and other organisms capable of horizontal gene transfer.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] Some research suggests that the average person has twice as many female ancestors as male ancestors.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] This might have been due to the past prevalence of polygynous relations and female hypergamy.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] Assuming that all of an individual's ancestors are otherwise unrelated to each other, that individual has 2*n* ancestors in the *n*th generation before them and a total of 2*g*+1 − 2 ancestors in the *g* generations before them.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] In practice, however, it is clear that most ancestors of humans (and any other species) are multiply related (see pedigree collapse).
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] Consider *n* = 40: the human species is more than 40 generations old, yet the number 240, approximately 1012 or one trillion, dwarfs the number of humans who have ever lived.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] Some cultures confer reverence to ancestors, both living and dead; in contrast, some more youth-oriented cultural contexts display less veneration of elders.
[src:anthropologist/ancestor] In other cultural contexts, ancestor worship or, more accurately, ancestor veneration is when people seek providence from their deceased ancestors.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] An **anthropologist** is a scientist engaged in the practice of anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropologists study aspects of humans within past and present societies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropologists are trying to understand the "big picture" of what it means to be human for a group of people in the world.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Social anthropology, cultural anthropology and philosophical anthropology study the norms, values, and general behavior of societies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Linguistic anthropology studies how language affects social life, while economic anthropology studies human economic behavior.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Biological (physical), forensic, and medical anthropology study the biology and evolution of humans and their primate relatives, the application of biological anthropology in a legal setting, and the study of diseases and their impacts on humans over time, respectively.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropologists usually cover a breadth of topics within anthropology in their undergraduate education and then proceed to specialize in topics of their own choice at the graduate level.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] In some universities, a qualifying exam serves to test both the breadth and depth of a student's understanding of anthropology; the students who pass are permitted to work on a doctoral dissertation.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropologists typically hold graduate degrees, either doctorates or master's degrees.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Not holding an advanced degree is rare in the field.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Some anthropologists hold undergraduate degrees in other fields than anthropology and graduate degrees in anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropological field work requires a faithful representation of observations and a strict adherence to social and ethical responsibilities, such as the acquisition of consent, transparency in research and methodologies and the right to anonymity.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Historically, anthropologists primarily worked in academic settings; however, by 2014, U.S. anthropologists and archaeologists were largely employed in research positions (28%), management and consulting (23%) and government positions (27%).
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] U.S. employment of anthropologists and archaeologists is projected to increase from 7,600 to 7,900 between 2016 and 2026, a growth rate just under half the national median.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropologists without doctorates tend to work more in other fields than academia, while the majority of those with doctorates are primarily employed in academia.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Many of those without doctorates in academia tend to work exclusively as researchers and do not teach.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Those in research-only positions are often not considered faculty.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] The median salary for anthropologists in 2015 was $62,220.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Many anthropologists report an above average level of job satisfaction.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Although closely related and often grouped with archaeology, anthropologists and archaeologists perform differing roles, though archeology is considered a sub-discipline of anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] While both professions focus on the study of human culture from past to present, archaeologists focus specifically on analyzing material remains such as artifacts and architectural remains.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropology encompasses a wider range of professions including the rising fields of forensic anthropology, digital anthropology and cyber anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] The role of an anthropologist differs as well from that of a historian.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] While anthropologists focus their studies on humans and human behavior, historians look at events from a broader perspective.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Historians also tend to focus less on culture than anthropologists in their studies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] A far greater percentage of historians are employed in academic settings than anthropologists, who have more diverse places of employment.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropologists are experiencing a shift in the twenty-first century United States with the rise of forensic anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] In the United States, as opposed to many other countries forensic anthropology falls under the domain of the anthropologist and not the Forensic pathologist.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] In this role, forensic anthropologists help in the identification of skeletal remains by deducing biological characteristics such as sex, age, stature and ancestry from the skeleton.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] However, forensic anthropologists tend to gravitate more toward working in academic and laboratory settings, while forensic pathologists perform more applied field work.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Forensic anthropologists typically hold academic doctorates, while forensic pathologists are medical doctors.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] The field of forensic anthropology is rapidly evolving with increasingly capable technology and more extensive databases.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Forensic anthropology is one of the most specialized and competitive job areas within the field of anthropology and currently has more qualified graduates than positions.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] The profession of Anthropology has also received an additional sub-field with the rise of Digital anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] This new branch of the profession has an increased usage of computers as well as interdisciplinary work with medicine, computer visualization, industrial design, biology and journalism.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropologists in this field primarily study the evolution of human reciprocal relations with the computer-generated world.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Cyber anthropologists also study digital and cyber ethics along with the global implications of increasing connectivity.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] With cyber ethical issues such as net neutrality increasingly coming to light, this sub-field is rapidly gaining more recognition.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] One rapidly emerging branch of interest for cyber anthropologists is artificial intelligence.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Cyber anthropologists study the co-evolutionary relationship between humans and artificial intelligence.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] This includes the examination of computer-generated (CG) environments and how people interact with them through media such as movies, television, and video.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] A central method anthropologists use is participant observation and having informal conversations with people.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Anthropologists take part in both observed conversations and participatory conversations.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Observed is where the anthropologist is observing a conversation that is happening without them directly involved.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] On the other hand, participatory conversations are where they are actually talking to the participant which can be in the form of an interview.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Cultural anthropology is a sub-field of anthropology specializing in the study of different cultures.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] They study both small-scale, traditional communities, such as isolated villages, and large-scale, modern societies, such as large cities.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] They look at different behaviors and patterns within a culture.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] In order to study these cultures, many anthropologists will live among the culture they are studying.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Cultural anthropologists can work as professors, work for corporations, nonprofit organizations, as well as government agencies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Linguistic anthropology is a sub-field of anthropology that specializes in the study of how random sounds eventually collect into meaningful language.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Linguistic anthropologists are the people studying ways in which language can create and sustain beliefs, relationships, and meaning in the world.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] In order to become a professional linguistic anthropologist, people obtain their doctorate degrees in anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] During the PhD, students take 3-4 years of coursework, including classes such as phonetics, morphology, and syntax.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Next, they acquire an in depth understanding of the history and society of a specific place in the world.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] After finishing their coursework and finishing exams, they move onto their fieldwork.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] There are job opportunities both in and out of academia.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Other jobs may include researching social media and information technology practices and policymaking for bilingual language education.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Another option is creating their own new language.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Some notable anthropologists include: Molefi Kete Asante, Ruth Benedict, Franz Boas, Ella Deloria, St.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Clair Drake, John Hope Franklin, James George Frazer, Clifford Geertz, Edward C.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] Green, Zora Neale Hurston, Claude Lévi-Strauss, Bronisław Malinowski, Margaret Mead, Elsie Clews Parsons, Pearl Primus, Paul Rabinow, Alfred Radcliffe-Brown, Marshall Sahlins, Nancy Scheper-Hughes (b.
[src:anthropologist/anthropologist] 1944), Hortense Spillers, Edward Burnett Tylor (1832–1917) and Frances Cress Welsing.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Archaeology, often referred to as the "anthropology of the past," explores human activity by examining physical remains.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In North America and Asia, it is generally regarded as a branch of anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In contrast, in Europe, it is considered either an independent discipline or a subfield of related disciplines such as history and palaeontology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The abstract noun *anthropology* is first attested in reference to history.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Its present use first appeared in Renaissance Germany in the works of Magnus Hundt and Otto Casmann.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Their Neo-Latin **anthropologia** derived from the combining forms of the Greek words *ánthrōpos* (ἄνθρωπος, "human") and *lógos* (λόγος, "study").
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Its adjectival form appeared in the works of Aristotle.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It began to be used in English, possibly via French **Anthropologie**, by the early 18th century.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Various short-lived organizations of anthropologists had already been formed.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The Société Ethnologique de Paris, the first to use the term *ethnology*, was founded in 1839 and focused on the methodical study of human races.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] After the death of its founder, William Frédéric Edwards, in 1842, it gradually declined in activity until it eventually dissolved in 1862.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Meanwhile, the Ethnological Society of New York, now the American Ethnological Society, was founded on its model in 1842, as well as the Ethnological Society of London in 1843, a break-away group of the Aborigines' Protection Society.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Anthropology and many other current fields are the intellectual results of the comparative methods developed in the early 19th century.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Theorists in diverse fields such as anatomy, linguistics, and ethnology started making feature-by-feature comparisons of their subject matters and were beginning to suspect that similarities between animals, languages, and folkways were the result of processes or laws unknown to them then.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] For them, the publication of Charles Darwin's *On the Origin of Species* was the epiphany of everything they had begun to suspect.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Darwin himself arrived at his conclusions through comparison of species he had seen in agronomy and in the wild.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Darwin and Wallace unveiled the theory of evolution in the late 1850s.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] There was an immediate rush to bring it into the social sciences.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Paul Broca in Paris was in the process of breaking away from the Société de biologie to form the first of the explicitly anthropological societies, the Société d'Anthropologie de Paris, meeting for the first time in Paris in 1859.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] When he read Darwin, he became an immediate convert to *Transformisme*, as the French called evolutionism.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] His definition now became "the study of the human group, considered as a whole, in its details, and in relation to the rest of nature".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Broca discovered the speech center of the human brain, today called Broca's area.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] His interest was mainly in biological anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Still, a German philosopher specializing in psychology, Theodor Waitz, took up the theme of general and social anthropology in his six-volume work, entitled *Die Anthropologie der Naturvölker*, 1859–1864.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The title was soon translated as "The Anthropology of Primitive Peoples".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The last two volumes were published posthumously.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Waitz defined anthropology as "the science of the nature of man".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Following Broca's lead, Waitz points out that anthropology is a new field that would gather material from other fields but would differ from them in its use of comparative anatomy, physiology, and psychology to differentiate man from "the animals nearest to him".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] He stresses that the data of comparison must be empirical, gathered by experimentation.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The history of civilization, as well as ethnology, is to be brought into the comparison.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is to be presumed fundamentally that the species, man, is a unity, and that "the same laws of thought are applicable to all men".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Waitz was influential among British ethnologists.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In 1863, the explorer Richard Francis Burton and the speech therapist James Hunt broke away from the Ethnological Society of London to form the Anthropological Society of London, which henceforward would follow the path of the new anthropology rather than just ethnology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It was the 2nd society dedicated to general anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Representatives from the French *Société* were present, though not Broca.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In his keynote address, printed in the first volume of its new publication, *The Anthropological Review*, Hunt stressed the work of Waitz, adopting his definitions as a standard.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Among the first associates were the young Edward Burnett Tylor, inventor of cultural anthropology, and his brother Alfred Tylor, a geologist.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Previously Edward had referred to himself as an ethnologist; subsequently, an anthropologist.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Similar organizations in other countries followed: the Anthropological Society of Madrid (1865), the American Anthropological Association (1902), the Anthropological Society of Vienna (1870), the Italian Society of Anthropology and Ethnology (1871), and many others.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The majority of these were evolutionists.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] One notable exception was the Berlin Society for Anthropology, Ethnology, and Prehistory (1869), founded by Rudolph Virchow, known for his vituperative attacks on the evolutionists.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Not religious himself, he insisted that Darwin's conclusions lacked empirical foundation.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] During the last three decades of the 19th century, a proliferation of anthropological societies and associations occurred, most independent, most publishing their own journals, and all international in membership and association.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The major theorists belonged to these organizations.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] They supported the gradual osmosis of anthropology curricula into the major institutions of higher learning.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] By 1898, 48 educational institutions in 13 countries offered some anthropology courses.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] None of the 75 faculty members were under a department named anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Some consider anthropology to have become a tool for colonisers, who study their subjects to gain a better understanding and control.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Anthropology, as a specialized field of academic study, developed significantly by the end of the 19th century.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Beginning in the early 20th century, the field saw rapid expansion, to the point where many of the world's higher education institutions typically included anthropology departments.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Thousands of anthropology departments have come into existence, and the field has diversified from a few major subdivisions to dozens more.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Practical anthropology, the use of anthropological knowledge and techniques to solve specific problems, has arrived; for example, the presence of buried victims might prompt the use of a forensic archaeologist to reconstruct the final scene.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The field has seen rapid growth on a global scale as well; the International Union of Anthropological and Ethnological Sciences contains members from over 50 countries.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Cultural anthropology, in particular, has emphasized cultural relativism, holism, and the use of findings to frame cultural critiques.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] This has been particularly prominent in the United States, from Boas' arguments against 19th-century racial ideology, through Margaret Mead's advocacy for gender equality and sexual liberation, to current criticisms of post-colonial oppression and promotion of multiculturalism.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnography is one of its primary research designs as well as the text that is generated from anthropological fieldwork.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In Great Britain and the Commonwealth countries, the British tradition of social anthropology tends to dominate.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In the United States, anthropology has traditionally been divided into the four field approach developed by Franz Boas in the early 20th century: *biological* or *physical* anthropology; *social*, *cultural*, or *sociocultural* anthropology; archaeological anthropology; and linguistic anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] These fields frequently overlap but tend to use different methodologies and techniques.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] European countries with overseas colonies tended to practice more ethnology (a term coined and defined by Adam F.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is sometimes referred to as sociocultural anthropology in parts of the world influenced by the European tradition.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Anthropology is a global discipline involving the humanities, social sciences, and natural sciences.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Early anthropology originated in Classical Greece and Persia and studied and tried to understand observable cultural diversity.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] As such, anthropology has been central in the development of several new (late 20th century) interdisciplinary fields such as cognitive science, global studies, and various ethnic studies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Sociocultural anthropology has been heavily influenced by structuralist and postmodern theories, as well as a shift toward the analysis of modern societies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] During the 1970s and 1990s, there was an epistemological shift away from the positivist traditions that had largely informed the discipline.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] During this shift, enduring questions about the nature and production of knowledge came to occupy a central place in cultural and social anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In contrast, archaeology and biological anthropology remained largely positivist.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Sociocultural anthropology draws together the principal axes of cultural anthropology and social anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Cultural anthropology is the comparative study of the manifold ways in which people *make sense* of the world around them.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In contrast, social anthropology is the study of the *relationships* among individuals and groups.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In that, it helps develop an understanding of social structures, typically of others and other populations (such as minorities, subgroups, dissidents, etc.).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] There is no hard-and-fast distinction between them, and these categories overlap to a considerable degree.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Inquiry in sociocultural anthropology is guided in part by cultural relativism, the attempt to understand other societies in terms of their own cultural symbols and values.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Accepting other cultures in their own terms moderates reductionism in cross-cultural comparison.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] This project is often accommodated in the field of ethnography.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnography can refer to both a methodology and the product of ethnographic research, i.e., an ethnographic monograph.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] As a methodology, ethnography is based upon long-term fieldwork within a community or other research site.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Participant observation is one of the foundational methods of social and cultural anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnology involves the systematic comparison of different cultures.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The process of participant observation can be especially helpful for understanding a culture from an emic (conceptual, vs. etic, or technical) point of view.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The study of kinship and social organization is a central focus of sociocultural anthropology, as kinship is a human universal.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Comparison across cultures is a key methodological element in sociocultural anthropology, including the industrialized (and de-industrialized) West.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The Standard Cross-Cultural Sample (SCCS) includes 186 such cultures.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Biological anthropology and physical anthropology are synonymous terms to describe anthropological research focused on the study of humans and other primates in their biological, evolutionary, and demographic dimensions.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It examines the biological and social factors that have affected the evolution of humans and other primates, and that generate, maintain or change contemporary genetic and physiological variation.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Subfields include forensic anthropology, paleoanthropology, dental anthropology, primatology, and human biology, among others.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Nineteenth- and twentieth-century America and Europe were formative periods for many scientific disciplines, and racism played a significant role in motivating certain avenues of research, including the early development of bioarchaeology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] This racist foundation shaped attitudes for decades, reinforcing the belief among many anthropologists that they held inherent authority over the human remains and burial sites they encountered.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Recognizing this history is crucial, as its effects persist today in the form of damaged evidence, ethical challenges, and harmful professional assumptions.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Archaeology is the study of the human past through its material remains.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Artifacts, faunal remains, and human-altered landscapes are evidence of the cultural and material lives of past societies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Archaeologists examine material remains to deduce patterns of past human behavior and cultural practices.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnoarchaeology is a branch of archaeology that studies the practices and material remains of living human groups to understand better the evidence left behind by past human groups presumed to have lived in similar ways.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Linguistic anthropology (not to be confused with anthropological linguistics) seeks to understand the processes of human communications, verbal and non-verbal, variation in language across time and space, the social uses of language, and the relationship between language and culture.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is the branch of anthropology that brings linguistic methods to bear on anthropological problems, linking the analysis of linguistic forms and processes to the interpretation of sociocultural processes.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Linguistic anthropologists often draw on related fields including sociolinguistics, pragmatics, cognitive linguistics, semiotics, discourse analysis, and narrative analysis.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnography is a method of analysing social or cultural interaction.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It often involves participant observation, though an ethnographer may also draw from texts written by participants in social interactions.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnography views first-hand experience and social context as important.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Tim Ingold distinguishes ethnography from anthropology, arguing that anthropology seeks to construct general theories of human experience applicable to novel settings, while ethnography concerns itself with fidelity.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] He argues that the anthropologist must make his writing consistent with their understanding of literature and other theory but notes that ethnography may be of use to the anthropologists and the fields inform one another.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] One of the central problems in the anthropology of art concerns the universality of 'art' as a cultural phenomenon.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Several anthropologists have noted that the Western categories of 'painting', 'sculpture', or 'literature', conceived as independent artistic activities, do not exist, or exist in a significantly different form, in most non-Western contexts.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] To solve this, anthropologists of art have focused on formal features in objects which, without exclusively being 'artistic', have certain evident 'aesthetic' qualities.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Boas' *Primitive Art*, Claude Lévi-Strauss' *The Way of the Masks* (1982) or Geertz's 'Art as Cultural System' (1983) are examples in this trend of transforming the anthropology of 'art' into an anthropology of culturally specific 'aesthetics'.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Media anthropology emphasizes ethnographic studies as a means of understanding producers, audiences, and other cultural and social aspects of mass media.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The types of ethnographic contexts explored range from media production (e.g., ethnographies of newspaper newsrooms, journalists in the field, and film production) to media reception, following audiences in their everyday responses to media.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Other types include cyber anthropology, a relatively new area of internet research, as well as ethnographies of other areas of research that involve media, such as development work, social movements, or health education.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] This is in addition to many classic ethnographic contexts, where media such as radio, the press, new media, and television have started to make their presences felt since the early 1990s.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnomusicology is an academic field encompassing various approaches to the study of music (broadly defined) that emphasize its cultural, social, material, cognitive, biological, and other dimensions or contexts, rather than its isolated sound component or any particular repertoire.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnomusicology can be applied across a wide range of fields, including teaching, politics, and cultural anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] While the origins of ethnomusicology date back to the 18th and 19th centuries, it was formally termed "ethnomusicology" by Dutch scholar Jaap Kunst c.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Later, the influence of study in this area spawned the creation of the periodical *Ethnomusicology* and the Society of Ethnomusicology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Visual anthropology is concerned, in part, with the study and production of ethnographic photography, film, and, since the mid-1990s, new media.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] While the term is sometimes used interchangeably with ethnographic film, visual anthropology also encompasses the anthropological study of visual representation, including areas such as performance, museums, art, and the production and reception of mass media.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Visual representations from all cultures, such as sandpaintings, tattoos, sculptures and reliefs, cave paintings, scrimshaw, jewelry, hieroglyphs, paintings, and photographs are included in the focus of visual anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Economic anthropology seeks to explain human economic behavior across the widest historical, geographic, and cultural scope.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It has a complex relationship with the discipline of economics, which it is highly critical of.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Its origins as a sub-field of anthropology begin with the Polish-British founder of anthropology, Bronisław Malinowski, and his French compatriot, Marcel Mauss, on the nature of gift-giving exchange (or reciprocity) as an alternative to market exchange.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Economic anthropology remains, for the most part, focused upon exchange.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The school of thought derived from Marx and known as political economy focuses on production, in contrast.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Economic anthropologists have abandoned the primitivist niche they were relegated to by economists, and have now turned to examine corporations, banks, and the global financial system from an anthropological perspective.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Political economy in anthropology is the application of the theories and methods of historical materialism to the traditional concerns of anthropology, including, but not limited to, non-capitalist societies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Political economy introduced questions of history and colonialism to ahistorical anthropological theories of social structure and culture.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Three main areas of interest rapidly developed.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The first of these areas concerned the "pre-capitalist" societies subject to evolutionary "tribal" stereotypes.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Sahlin's work on hunter-gatherers as the "original affluent society" did much to dissipate that image.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The second area was concerned with the vast majority of the world's population at the time, the peasantry, many of whom were involved in complex revolutionary wars, such as in Vietnam.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The third area was on colonialism, imperialism, and the creation of the capitalist world-system.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] More recently, these political economists have more directly addressed issues of industrial (and post-industrial) capitalism around the world.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Applied anthropology refers to the application of the method and theory of anthropology to the analysis and solution of practical problems.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is a "complex of related, research-based, instrumental methods which produce change or stability in specific cultural systems through the provision of data, initiation of direct action, and/or the formulation of policy".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Applied anthropology is the practical side of anthropological research; it includes researcher involvement and activism within the participating community.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is closely related to development anthropology (distinct from the more critical anthropology of development).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Anthropology of development tends to view development from a *critical* perspective.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The issues addressed, and the implications for the approach, involve pondering why, if a key development goal is to alleviate poverty, poverty is increasing.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Why is there such a gap between plans and outcomes?
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Why are those working in development so willing to disregard history and the lessons it might offer?
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Why is development so externally driven rather than having an internal basis?
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In short, why does so much planned development fail?
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Feminist anthropology is a four-field approach to anthropology (archeological, biological, cultural, linguistic) that seeks to reduce male bias in research findings, anthropological hiring practices, and the scholarly production of knowledge.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Anthropology often engages with feminists from non-Western traditions, whose perspectives and experiences can differ from those of white feminists of Europe, America, and elsewhere.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] From the perspective of the Western world, such 'peripheral' perspectives have historically been ignored, viewed only from an outsider's perspective, and regarded as less valid or less important than knowledge from the Western world.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Exploring and addressing that double bias against women from marginalized racial or ethnic groups is of particular interest in intersectional feminist anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] This correction of systemic bias may include mainstream feminist theory, history, linguistics, archaeology, and anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Feminist anthropologists are often concerned with the construction of gender across societies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Gender constructs are of particular interest in the study of sexism.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Clair Drake, Vera Mae Green was, until "[w]ell into the 1960s", the only African American female anthropologist who was also a Caribbeanist.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] She studied ethnic and family relations in the Caribbean and the United States, and thereby sought to improve the way black life, experiences, and culture were studied.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] However, Zora Neale Hurston, although often primarily considered to be a literary author, was trained in anthropology by Franz Boas, and published *Tell my Horse* about her "anthropological observations" of voodoo in the Caribbean (1938).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Feminist anthropology is inclusive of the anthropology of birth as a specialization, which is the anthropological study of pregnancy and childbirth within cultures and societies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Medical anthropology is an interdisciplinary field that studies "human health and disease, health care systems, and biocultural adaptation".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is believed that William Caudell was the first to discover the field of medical anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Currently, research in medical anthropology is one of the main areas of growth in anthropology as a whole.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Other subjects that have become central to medical anthropology worldwide are violence and social suffering (Farmer, 1999, 2003; Beneduce, 2010), as well as other issues that involve physical and psychological harm and suffering that are not a result of illness.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] On the other hand, some fields intersect with medical anthropology in research methodology and theoretical production, such as *cultural psychiatry*, *transcultural psychiatry*, and *ethnopsychiatry*.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Nutritional anthropology is a synthetic concept that examines the interplay among economic systems, nutritional status, and food security, and how changes in the former affect the latter.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] If economic and environmental changes in a community affect access to food, food security, and dietary health, then this interplay between culture and biology is in turn connected to broader historical and economic trends associated with globalization.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Nutritional status affects overall health, work performance potential, and the potential for economic development (whether in terms of human development or traditional Western models) for any given group of people.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Psychological anthropology is an interdisciplinary subfield of anthropology that studies the interaction of cultural and mental processes.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] This subfield tends to focus on ways in which humans' development and enculturation within a particular cultural group – with its own history, language, practices, and conceptual categories – shape processes of human cognition, emotion, perception, motivation, and mental health.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It also examines how the understanding of cognition, emotion, motivation, and similar psychological processes inform or constrain our models of cultural and social processes.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Cognitive anthropology is concerned with what people from different groups know and how that implicit knowledge shapes how they perceive and relate to the world around them.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Transpersonal anthropology studies the relationship between altered states of consciousness and culture.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] As with transpersonal psychology, the field is much concerned with altered states of consciousness (ASC) and transpersonal experience.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] However, the field differs from mainstream transpersonal psychology in taking more cognizance of cross-cultural issues – for instance, the roles of myth, ritual, diet, and text in evoking and interpreting extraordinary experiences.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Political anthropology concerns the structure of political systems, viewed in light of the structure of societies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The turn towards complex societies meant that political themes were taken up at two main levels.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Firstly, anthropologists continued to study political organization and political phenomena that lay outside the state-regulated sphere (as in patron-client relations or tribal political organization).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Secondly, anthropologists gradually began to develop a disciplinary concern with states and their institutions (and with the relationship between formal and informal political institutions).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] An anthropology of the state has developed into a thriving field today.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Geertz's comparative work on "Negara", the Balinese state, is an early, famous example.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Legal anthropology or anthropology of law specializes in "the cross-cultural study of social ordering".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Earlier legal anthropological research often focused more narrowly on conflict management, crime, sanctions, or formal regulation.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] More recent applications include issues such as human rights, legal pluralism, and political uprisings.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Cyborg anthropology originated as a sub-focus group within the American Anthropological Association's annual meeting in 1993.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The sub-group was very closely related to STS and the Society for the Social Studies of Science.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Donna Haraway's 1985 *Cyborg Manifesto* could be considered the founding document of cyborg anthropology, as it first explores the philosophical and sociological ramifications of the term.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Cyborg anthropology studies humankind and its relations with the technological systems it has built, specifically modern systems that have reflexively shaped notions of what it means to be human.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Digital anthropology is the study of the relationship between humans and digital-era technology and extends to various areas where anthropology and technology intersect.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is sometimes grouped with sociocultural anthropology, and sometimes considered part of material culture.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The field is new and thus has a variety of names and emphases.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] These include techno-anthropology, digital ethnography, cyberanthropology, and virtual anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ecological anthropology is defined as the "study of cultural adaptations to environments".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The sub-field is also defined as, "the study of relationships between a population of humans and their biophysical environment".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The focus of its research concerns "how cultural beliefs and practices helped human populations adapt to their environments, and how their environments change across space and time.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The contemporary perspective of environmental anthropology, and arguably at least the backdrop, if not the focus of most of the ethnographies and cultural fieldworks of today, is political ecology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Many characterize this new perspective as more informed with culture, politics, and power, globalization, localized issues, century anthropology, and more.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The focus and data interpretation is often used for arguments for/against or creation of policy, and to prevent corporate exploitation and damage of land.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Often, the observer has become an active part of the struggle, either directly (organizing, participating) or indirectly (through articles, documentaries, books, ethnographies).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Such is the case with environmental justice advocate Melissa Checker and her relationship with the people of Hyde Park.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Social sciences, such as anthropology, can offer interdisciplinary approaches to environmental issues.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Professor Kay Milton, Director of the Anthropology research network in the School of History and Anthropology, describes anthropology as distinctive, with its most distinguishing feature being its interest in non-industrial indigenous and traditional societies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Anthropological theory is distinct because of the consistent presence of the concept of culture; not an exclusive topic but a central position in the study and a deep concern with the human condition.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Environmental discourse appears to be characterized by a high degree of globalization.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] (The troubling problem is borrowing non-indigenous practices and creating standards, concepts, philosophies, and practices in Western countries.) Anthropology and environmental discourse have now become a distinct position in anthropology as a discipline.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Knowledge about diversities in human culture can be important in addressing environmental problems - anthropology is now a study of human ecology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Human activity is the most important agent in creating environmental change, a finding commonly found in human ecology, and it can claim a central place in how environmental problems are examined and addressed.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Other ways anthropology contributes to environmental discourse include serving as theorists and analysts, or refining definitions to be more neutral/universal, etc.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In the context of environmentalism, the term typically refers to the concern that the environment should be protected, particularly from the harmful effects of human activities.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Environmentalism itself can be expressed in many ways.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnohistory is the study of ethnographic cultures and indigenous customs through the examination of historical records.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is also the study of the history of various ethnic groups that may or may not exist today.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ethnohistory uses both historical and ethnographic data as its foundation.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Its historical methods and materials go beyond the standard use of documents and manuscripts.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Practitioners recognize the utility of such source material as maps, music, paintings, photography, folklore, oral tradition, site exploration, archaeological materials, museum collections, enduring customs, language, and place names.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The anthropology of religion involves the study of religious institutions in relation to other social institutions, and the comparison of religious beliefs and practices across cultures.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Modern anthropology assumes that there is complete continuity between magical thinking and religion, and that every religion is a cultural product created by the human community that worships it.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Urban anthropology is concerned with issues of urbanization, poverty, and neoliberalism.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Ulf Hannerz quotes a 1960s remark that traditional anthropologists were "a notoriously agoraphobic lot, anti-urban by definition".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Various social processes in the Western World as well as in the "Third World" (the latter being the habitual focus of attention of anthropologists) brought the attention of "specialists in 'other cultures'" closer to their homes.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] There are two main approaches to urban anthropology: examining the types of cities or examining the social issues within the cities.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] These two methods overlap and depend on each other.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] When defining different types of cities, one would use social, economic, and political factors to categorize them.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] By directly looking at the different social issues, one would also be studying how they affect the dynamic of the city.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Anthrozoology (also known as "human–animal studies") is the study of the interaction between living things.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is an interdisciplinary field that overlaps with several other disciplines, including anthropology, ethology, medicine, psychology, veterinary medicine, and zoology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] A major focus of anthrozoologic research is the quantification of the positive effects of human-animal relationships on either party and the study of their interactions.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It includes scholars from a diverse range of fields, including anthropology, sociology, biology, and philosophy.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Biocultural anthropology is the scientific exploration of the relationships between human biology and culture.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Physical anthropologists throughout the first half of the 20th century viewed this relationship from a racial perspective; that is, from the assumption that typological human biological differences lead to cultural differences.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] After World War II the emphasis began to shift toward an effort to explore the role culture plays in shaping human biology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Evolutionary anthropology is the interdisciplinary study of the evolution of human physiology and human behaviour and the relation between hominins and non-hominin primates.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Evolutionary anthropology is based in natural science and social science, combining the human development with socioeconomic factors.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Evolutionary anthropology is concerned with both the biological and cultural evolution of humans, past and present.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is based on a scientific approach, and brings together fields such as archaeology, behavioral ecology, psychology, primatology, and genetics.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is a dynamic and interdisciplinary field, drawing on many lines of evidence to understand the human experience, past and present.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Forensic anthropology is the application of the science of physical anthropology and human osteology in a legal setting, most often in criminal cases where the victim's remains are in the advanced stages of decomposition.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] A forensic anthropologist can assist in the identification of deceased individuals whose remains are decomposed, burned, mutilated, or otherwise unrecognizable.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The adjective "forensic" refers to the application of this subfield of science to a court of law.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Paleoanthropology combines the disciplines of paleontology and physical anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] It is the study of ancient humans, as evidenced by fossil hominid remains, such as petrifacted bones and footprints.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The genetics and morphology of specimens are crucial to this field.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Markers on specimens, such as enamel fractures and dental decay on teeth, can also give insight into the behaviour and diet of past populations.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Contemporary anthropology is an established science with academic departments at most universities and colleges.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The largest organization of anthropologists is the American Anthropological Association (AAA), founded in 1903.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] Its members are anthropologists from around the globe.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] In 1989, a group of European and American scholars in anthropology established the European Association of Social Anthropologists (EASA), which serves as a major professional organization for anthropologists working in Europe.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p01] The EASA seeks to advance the status of anthropology in Europe and to increase the visibility of marginalized anthropological traditions, thereby contributing to the project of a global or world anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] As the field has matured, it has debated and arrived at ethical principles aimed at protecting both the subjects of anthropological research and the researchers themselves, and professional societies have generated codes of ethics.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Anthropologists, like other researchers (especially historians and scientists engaged in field research), have over time assisted state policies and projects, especially colonialism.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] As part of their quest for scientific objectivity, present-day anthropologists typically advocate cultural relativism, which influences all subfields of anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] This is the notion that cultures should not be judged by another's values or viewpoints, but be examined dispassionately on their own terms.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] There should be no notions, in good anthropology, of one culture being better or worse than another culture.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Ethical commitments in anthropology include noticing and documenting genocide, infanticide, racism, sexism, mutilation (including circumcision and subincision), and torture.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Topics like racism, slavery, and human sacrifice attract anthropological attention and theories ranging from nutritional deficiencies, to genes, to acculturation, to colonialism, have been proposed to explain their origins and continued recurrences.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] To illustrate the depth of an anthropological approach, one can take just one of these topics, such as racism, and find thousands of anthropological references spanning all major and minor subfields.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Anthropologists' involvement with the U.S. government, in particular, has caused bitter controversy within the discipline.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Franz Boas publicly objected to US participation in World War I, and after the war, he published a brief exposé and condemnation of the participation of several American archaeologists in espionage in Mexico under their cover as scientists.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] But by the 1940s, many of Boas' anthropologist contemporaries were active in the Allied war effort against the Axis powers (Nazi Germany, Fascist Italy, and Imperial Japan).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Many served in the armed forces, while others worked in intelligence (for example, the Office of Strategic Services and the Office of War Information).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Price's work on American anthropology during the Cold War provides detailed accounts of the pursuit and dismissal of several anthropologists from their jobs based on communist sympathies.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Attempts to accuse anthropologists of complicity with the CIA and government intelligence activities during the Vietnam War years have turned up little.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Many anthropologists (students and teachers) were active in the anti-war movement.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Numerous resolutions condemning the war in all its aspects were passed overwhelmingly at the annual meetings of the American Anthropological Association (AAA).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Professional anthropological bodies often object to the use of anthropology for the benefit of the state.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Their codes of ethics or statements may proscribe anthropologists from giving secret briefings.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] The Association of Social Anthropologists of the UK and Commonwealth (ASA) has called certain scholarship ethically dangerous.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Anthropologists, along with other social scientists, were working with the US military as part of the US Army's strategy in Afghanistan.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] *The Christian Science Monitor* reports that "Counterinsurgency efforts focus on better grasping and meeting local needs" in Afghanistan, under the *Human Terrain System* (HTS) program; in addition, HTS teams are working with the US military in Iraq.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Before WWII, British 'social anthropology' and American 'cultural anthropology' were still distinct traditions.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] After the war, enough British and American anthropologists borrowed ideas and methodological approaches from one another that some began to speak of them collectively as 'sociocultural' anthropology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Several characteristics tend to unite anthropological work.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] One of the central characteristics is that anthropology tends to provide a more holistic account of phenomena and is highly empirical.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] The quest for holism leads most anthropologists to study a particular place, problem, or phenomenon in detail, using a variety of methods, over a more extensive period than normal in many parts of academia.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] In the 1990s and 2000s, calls for clarification of what constitutes a culture, of how an observer knows where their own culture ends and another begins, and other crucial topics in writing anthropology were heard.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] These dynamic relationships between what can be observed on the ground and what can be inferred from compiling many local observations remain fundamental to any anthropology, whether cultural, biological, linguistic, or archaeological.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Biological anthropologists are interested in both human variation and in the possibility of human universals (behaviors, ideas, or concepts shared by virtually all human cultures).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] They use many different methods of study.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Along with dividing up their project by theoretical emphasis, anthropologists typically divide the world into relevant time periods and geographic regions.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Time periods are divided into relevant cultural traditions based on material culture, such as the Paleolithic and the Neolithic, which are of particular use in archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Further cultural subdivisions by tool type, such as Oldowan, Mousterian, or Levalloisian, help archaeologists and other anthropologists understand major trends in the past.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Anthropologists and geographers also share approaches to culture regions, since mapping cultures is central to both sciences.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] By making comparisons across cultural traditions (time-based) and cultural regions (space-based), anthropologists have developed various kinds of comparative method, a central part of their science.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Some authors argue that anthropology originated and developed as the study of "other cultures", both in terms of time (past societies) and space (non-European/non-Western societies).
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Now there exist many works focusing on peoples and topics very close to the author's "home".
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] It is also argued that other fields of study, like History and Sociology, on the contrary focus disproportionately on the West.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] Since the 1980s, it has become common for social and cultural anthropologists to set ethnographic research in the North Atlantic region, frequently examining the connections between locations rather than limiting research to a single locale.
[src:anthropologist/anthropology-p02] There has also been a related shift toward broadening the focus beyond the daily life of ordinary people; increasingly, research is set in settings such as scientific laboratories, social movements, governmental and nongovernmental organizations, and businesses.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeologists study human prehistory and history, from the development of the first stone tools at Lomekwi in East Africa 3.3 million years ago up until recent decades.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeology is distinct from palaeontology, which is the study of fossil remains.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeology is particularly important for learning about prehistoric societies, for which, by definition, there are no written records.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Prehistory includes over 99% of the human past, from the Paleolithic until the advent of literacy in societies around the world.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeology has various goals, ranging from understanding culture history to reconstructing past lifeways to documenting and explaining changes in human societies over time.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Derived from Greek, the term *archaeology* means "the study of ancient history".
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeology developed out of antiquarianism in Europe during the 19th century and has since become a discipline practiced worldwide.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Nation-states have used archaeology to create particular visions of the past.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Since its early development, various specific sub-disciplines of archaeology have developed, including maritime archaeology, feminist archaeology, and archaeoastronomy, and numerous different scientific techniques have been developed to aid archaeological investigation.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Nonetheless, today, archaeologists face many problems, such as dealing with pseudoarchaeology, the looting of artifacts, a lack of public interest, and opposition to the excavation of human remains.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In Ancient Mesopotamia, a foundation deposit of the Akkadian Empire ruler Naram-Sin (ruled c.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] 2200 BC) was discovered and analysed by king Nabonidus, c.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] 550 BC, who is thus known as the first archaeologist.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] He was also the first to date an archaeological artifact in his attempt to date Naram-Sin's temple during his search for it.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Even though his estimate was inaccurate by about 1,500 years, it was still a very good one considering the lack of accurate dating technology at the time.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The science of archaeology (from Greek ἀρχαιολογία *archaiologia*, from ἀρχαῖος, *arkhaios* 'ancient' and -λογία, *-logia* 'study') grew out of the older multi-disciplinary study known as antiquarianism.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Antiquarians studied history with particular attention to ancient artifacts, manuscripts, and historical sites.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Antiquarianism focused on the empirical evidence available for understanding the past, encapsulated in the motto of the 18th century antiquary Richard Colt Hoare: "We speak from facts, not theory".
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Tentative steps towards the systematization of archaeology as a science took place during the Enlightenment period in Europe in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In Imperial China during the Song dynasty (960–1279), figures such as Ouyang Xiu and Zhao Mingcheng established the tradition of Chinese epigraphy by investigating, preserving, and analyzing ancient Chinese bronze inscriptions from the Shang and Zhou periods.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Such antiquarian pursuits waned after the Song period, were revived in the 17th century during the Qing dynasty, but were always considered a branch of Chinese historiography rather than a separate discipline of archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In Renaissance Europe, philosophical interest in the remains of Greco-Roman civilization and the rediscovery of classical culture began in the late Middle Ages, with humanism.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Cyriacus of Ancona was a restlessly itinerant Italian humanist and antiquarian who came from a prominent family of merchants in Ancona, a maritime republic on the Adriatic.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] He noted down his archaeological discoveries in his diary, *Commentaria* (in six volumes).
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Flavio Biondo, an Italian Renaissance humanist historian, created a systematic guide to the ruins and topography of ancient Rome in the early 15th century, for which he has been called an early founder of archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Antiquarians of the 16th century, including John Leland and William Camden, conducted surveys of the English countryside, drawing, describing and interpreting the monuments that they encountered.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* first cites "archaeologist" in 1824; this soon became the usual term for one major branch of antiquarian activity.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] "Archaeology", from 1607 onward, initially meant what we would call "ancient history" generally, with the narrower modern sense first seen in 1837.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Twelfth-century Indian scholar Kalhana's writings involved recording local traditions and examining manuscripts, inscriptions, coins, and architecture, which are described as among the earliest traces of archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] One of his notable works is called *Rajatarangini*, which was completed c.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] 1150 and is considered one of the first historical works of India.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Among the first sites to undergo archaeological excavation were Stonehenge and other megalithic monuments in England.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] John Aubrey (1626–1697) was a pioneer archaeologist who recorded numerous megalithic and other field monuments in southern England.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] He was also ahead of his time in analysing his findings.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] He attempted to chart the chronological stylistic evolution of handwriting, medieval architecture, costume, and shield-shapes.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Excavations were also carried out by the Spanish military engineer Roque Joaquín de Alcubierre in the ancient towns of Pompeii and Herculaneum, both of which had been covered by ash during the Eruption of Mount Vesuvius in AD 79.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] These excavations began in 1748 in Pompeii and in 1738 in Herculaneum.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The discovery of entire towns, complete with utensils and even human shapes, as well as the unearthing of frescos, had a big impact throughout Europe.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] However, before the development of modern techniques, excavations tended to be haphazard; the importance of concepts such as stratification and context was overlooked.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In the mid-18th century, the German Johann Joachim Winckelmann lived in Rome and devoted himself to the study of Roman antiquities, gradually acquiring an unrivalled knowledge of ancient art.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Then, he visited the archaeological excavations being conducted at Pompeii and Herculaneum.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] He was one of the founders of scientific archaeology and first applied the categories of style on a large, systematic basis to the history of art.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] He was one of the first to separate Greek art into periods and time classifications.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Winckelmann has been called both "The prophet and founding hero of modern archaeology" and the father of the discipline of art history.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The father of archaeological excavation was William Cunnington (1754–1810).
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] He undertook excavations in Wiltshire from around 1798, funded by Sir Richard Colt Hoare.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Cunnington made meticulous recordings of Neolithic and Bronze Age barrows, and the terms he used to categorize and describe them are still used by archaeologists today.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] President Thomas Jefferson also did his own excavations in 1784 using the trench method, on several Native American burial mounds in Virginia.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] His excavations were prompted by the "Moundbuilders" question; however, his careful methods led him to conclude that there was no reason why the ancestors of the Native Americans of his time could not have raised those mounds.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] One of the major achievements of 19th-century archaeology was the development of stratigraphy.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The idea of overlapping strata tracing back to successive periods was borrowed from the new geological and palaeontological work of scholars like William Smith, James Hutton, and Charles Lyell.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The systematic application of stratigraphy to archaeology first occurred during excavations of prehistorical and Bronze Age sites.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In the third and fourth decades of the 19th century, archaeologists such as Jacques Boucher de Perthes and Christian Jürgensen Thomsen began to arrange the artifacts they had found in chronological order.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] A major figure in the development of archaeology into a rigorous science was army officer and ethnologist Augustus Pitt Rivers, who began excavations on his land in England in the 1880s.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Highly methodical by the standards of the time, he is widely regarded as the first scientific archaeologist.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] He arranged his artifacts by type or "Typology (archaeology)", and within types chronologically.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This style of arrangement, designed to highlight evolutionary trends in human artifacts, was of enormous significance for accurately dating the objects.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] His most important methodological innovation was his insistence that *all* artifacts, not just beautiful or unique ones, be collected and catalogued.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] William Flinders Petrie is another man who may legitimately be called the Father of Archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Petrie was the first to scientifically investigate the Great Pyramid in Egypt during the 1880s.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] He was also responsible for mentoring and training a whole generation of Egyptologists, including Howard Carter who went on to achieve fame with the discovery of the tomb of 14th-century BC pharaoh Tutankhamun.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The first stratigraphic excavation to gain wide public popularity was that of Hissarlik, on the site of ancient Troy, carried out by Heinrich Schliemann, Frank Calvert, and Wilhelm Dörpfeld in the 1870s.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] These scholars individuated nine different cities that had overlapped with one another, from prehistory to the Hellenistic period.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Meanwhile, the work of Sir Arthur Evans at Knossos in Crete revealed the ancient existence of an equally advanced Minoan civilization.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The next major figure in the development of archaeology was Sir Mortimer Wheeler, whose highly disciplined approach to excavation and systematic coverage in the 1920s and 1930s brought the science on swiftly.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Wheeler developed the grid system of excavation, which was further improved by his student Kathleen Kenyon.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeology became a professional activity in the first half of the 20th century, and it became possible to study archaeology as a subject in universities and even schools.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] By the end of the 20th century, nearly all professional archaeologists, at least in developed countries, were graduates.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Further adaptation and innovation in archaeology continued in this period, when maritime archaeology and urban archaeology became more prevalent, and rescue archaeology was developed in response to increasing commercial development.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The purpose of archaeology is to learn more about past societies and the development of the human race.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Over 99% of human development has occurred within prehistoric cultures, which did not use writing; no written records exist for study.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Without such written sources, the only way to understand prehistoric societies is through archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Because archaeology is the study of past human activity, it stretches back to about 2.5 million years ago when the first stone tools were found – The Oldowan Industry.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Many important developments in human history occurred during prehistory, such as the evolution of humanity during the Paleolithic period, when the hominins developed from the australopithecines in Africa and eventually into modern *Homo sapiens*.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeology also sheds light on many of humanity's technological advances, for instance, the ability to use fire, the development of stone tools, the discovery of metallurgy, the beginnings of religion, and the creation of agriculture.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Without archaeology, little or nothing would be known about humanity's use of material culture that predates writing.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] However, it is not only prehistoric, pre-literate cultures that can be studied using archaeology; historic, literate cultures can also be studied through the sub-discipline of historical archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] For many literate cultures, such as Ancient Greece and Mesopotamia, their surviving records are often incomplete and biased to some extent.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In many societies, literacy was restricted to the elite classes, such as the clergy or the bureaucracy of the court or the temple.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The literacy of aristocrats has sometimes been restricted to deeds and contracts.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The interests and worldview of elites are often quite different from those of the populace.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Writings that were produced by people more representative of the general population were unlikely to find their way into libraries and be preserved there for posterity.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Thus, written records tend to reflect the biases, assumptions, cultural values, and possibly deceptions of a limited range of individuals, usually a small fraction of the larger population.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Hence, written records cannot be trusted as a sole source.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The material record may be closer to a fair representation of society, though it is subject to its own biases, such as sampling bias and differential preservation.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Often, archaeology provides the only means of learning about the existence and behavior of people in the past.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Over the millennia, many thousands of cultures and societies, and billions of people, have come and gone, with little or no written record, or with existing records that are misrepresentative or incomplete.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Writing, as it is known today, did not exist in human civilization until the 4th millennium BC, and even then, only in a relatively small number of technologically advanced civilizations.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In contrast, *Homo sapiens* has existed for at least 200,000 years, and other *Homo* species for millions of years (see Human evolution).
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] These civilizations are, not coincidentally, the best known; they have been open to historical inquiry for centuries, whereas the study of prehistoric cultures has only recently emerged.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Within a literate civilization, many events and important human practices may not be officially recorded.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Any knowledge of the early years of human civilization – the development of agriculture, cult practices of folk religion, the rise of the first cities – must come from archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In addition to their scientific importance, archaeological remains sometimes have political or cultural significance for the descendants of the people who produced them, monetary value for collectors, or strong aesthetic appeal.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Many people identify archaeology with the recovery of such aesthetic, religious, political, or economic treasures rather than with the reconstruction of past societies.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This view is often espoused in works of popular fiction, such as Raiders of the Lost Ark, The Mummy, and King Solomon's Mines.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] When unrealistic subjects are treated more seriously, accusations of pseudoscience are invariably levelled at their proponents *(see Pseudoarchaeology)*.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] However, these endeavours, real and fictional, are not representative of modern archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] There is no single approach to archaeological theory adopted by all archaeologists.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In the 1960s, an archaeological movement largely led by American archaeologists like Lewis Binford and Kent Flannery arose that rebelled against the established cultural-history archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] They proposed a "New Archaeology", which would be more "scientific" and "anthropological", with hypothesis testing and the scientific method very important parts of what became known as processual archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In the 1980s, a new postmodern movement arose led by the British archaeologists Michael Shanks, Christopher Tilley, Daniel Miller, and Ian Hodder, which has become known as post-processual archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It questioned processualism's appeals to scientific positivism and impartiality; it emphasized the importance of a more self-critical theoretical reflexivity.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] However, processualists have criticized this approach as lacking scientific rigour.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The validity of both processualism and post-processualism is still under debate.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Meanwhile, another theory, known as historical processualism, has emerged seeking to incorporate a focus on process and post-processual archaeology's emphasis on reflexivity and history.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] An archaeological investigation usually involves several distinct phases, each employing a variety of methods.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Before any practical work can begin, however, a clear objective for what the archaeologists are seeking to achieve must be agreed upon.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This done, a site is surveyed to learn as much as possible about it and its surroundings.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Second, an excavation may be conducted to uncover any buried archaeological features.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] And third, the information collected during the excavation is studied and evaluated to achieve the archaeologists' original research objectives.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It is then considered good practice for the information to be published so that it is available to other archaeologists and historians, although this is sometimes neglected.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Before actually starting to dig at a location, remote sensing can be used to identify where sites are located within a large area or to provide more information about sites or regions.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] There are two types of remote sensing instruments—passive and active.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Passive instruments detect natural energy reflected or emitted by the observed scene.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Passive instruments sense only radiation emitted by the object being viewed or reflected by the object from a source other than the instrument.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Active instruments emit energy and record the reflections.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Satellite imagery is an example of passive remote sensing.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The distance to the object is determined by recording the time between the transmitted and backscattered pulses and using the speed of light to calculate the distance travelled.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Lidars can determine atmospheric profiles of aerosols, clouds, and other atmospheric constituents.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The archaeological project then continues (or begins) with a field survey.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] A regional survey is an attempt to locate previously unknown sites within a region systematically.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] A site survey is an attempt to systematically locate features of interest, such as houses and middens, within a site.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Each of these two goals may be accomplished with largely the same methods.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Surveys were not widely practised in the early days of archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Cultural historians and earlier researchers were usually content to discover the locations of monumental sites from the local populace and to excavate only the plainly visible features there.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Gordon Willey pioneered the technique of regional settlement pattern survey in 1949 in the Viru Valley of coastal Peru, and survey of all levels became prominent with the rise of processual archaeology some years later.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Survey work has many benefits if performed as a preliminary exercise to, or even in place of, excavation.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It requires relatively little time and expense because it does not involve processing large volumes of soil to search for artifacts.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] (Nevertheless, surveying a large region or site can be expensive, so archaeologists often employ sampling methods.) As with other forms of non-destructive archaeology, survey avoids ethical issues (of particular concern to descendant peoples) associated with destroying a site through excavation.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It is the only way to gather some forms of information, such as settlement patterns and settlement structure.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Survey data are commonly assembled into maps, which may show surface features and/or artifact distribution.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The simplest survey technique is a surface survey.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It involves combing an area, usually on foot but sometimes using mechanized transport, to search for features or artifacts visible on the surface.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Surface survey cannot detect sites or features that are completely buried under earth or overgrown with vegetation.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Surface survey may also include mini-excavation techniques such as augers, corers, and shovel test pits.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] If no materials are found, the area surveyed is deemed sterile.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Aerial survey is conducted using cameras attached to airplanes, balloons, UAVs, or even Kites.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] A bird's-eye view is useful for quick mapping of large or complex sites.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Aerial photographs are used to document the status of the archaeological dig.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Aerial imaging can also detect many things not visible from the surface.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Plants growing above a buried human-made structure, such as a stone wall, will develop more slowly, while those above other types of features (such as middens) may develop more rapidly.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Photographs of ripening grain, which changes colour rapidly at maturation, have revealed buried structures with great precision.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Aerial photographs taken at different times of day will help show the outlines of structures by changes in shadows.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Aerial survey also employs ultraviolet, infrared, ground-penetrating radar wavelengths, Lidar and thermography.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Geophysical survey can be the most effective way to see beneath the ground.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Magnetometers detect minute deviations in the Earth's magnetic field caused by iron artifacts, kilns, some types of stone structures, and even ditches and middens.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Devices that measure the electrical resistivity of the soil are also widely used.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeological features whose electrical resistivity contrasts with that of surrounding soils can be detected and mapped.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Some archaeological features (such as those composed of stone or brick) have higher resistivity than typical soils.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In comparison, others (such as organic deposits or unfired clay) tend to have lower resistivity.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Although some archaeologists consider the use of metal detectors to be tantamount to treasure hunting, others deem them an effective tool in archaeological surveying.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Examples of formal archaeological use of metal detectors include musketball distribution analysis on English Civil War battlefields, metal distribution analysis before excavation of a 19th-century ship wreck, and service cable location during evaluation.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Metal detectorists have also contributed to archaeology, where they have made detailed records of their results and refrained from raising artifacts from their archaeological context.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In the UK, metal detectorists have been invited to participate in the Portable Antiquities Scheme.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Regional survey in underwater archaeology uses geophysical or remote sensing devices such as a marine magnetometer, side-scan sonar, or sub-bottom sonar.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeological excavation has existed even when the field was still the domain of amateurs, and it remains the primary source of data recovered in most field projects.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It can reveal several types of information that are usually not accessible through surveys, such as stratigraphy, three-dimensional structure, and verifiably primary context.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Modern excavation techniques require that the precise locations of objects and features, known as their provenance or provenience, be recorded.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This always involves determining their horizontal locations and, sometimes, their vertical positions as well (see also Primary Laws of Archaeology).
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Likewise, their association, or relationship with nearby objects and features, needs to be recorded for later analysis.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This allows the archaeologist to deduce which artifacts and features were likely used together and which may be from different phases of activity.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] For example, excavation of a site reveals its stratigraphy; if a succession of distinct cultures occupied a site, artifacts from more recent cultures will lie above those from earlier ones.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Excavation is the most expensive phase of archaeological research, in relative terms.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Also, as a destructive process, it carries ethical concerns.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] As a result, very few sites are excavated in their entirety.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Again, the percentage of a site excavated depends greatly on the country and the "method statement" issued.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Sampling is even more important in excavation than in survey.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Sometimes large mechanical equipment, such as backhoes (JCBs), is used in excavation, especially to remove the topsoil (overburden), though this method is increasingly used with great caution.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Following this rather dramatic step, the exposed area is usually hand-cleaned with trowels or hoes to ensure that all features are apparent.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The next task is to create a site plan and then use it to help determine the excavation method.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Features dug into the natural subsoil are normally excavated in portions to produce a visible archaeological section for recording.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] A feature, for example, a pit or a ditch, consists of two parts: the cut and the fill.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The cut describes the edge of the feature where it meets the natural soil.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The fill is what the feature is filled with, and will often appear quite distinct from the natural soil.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The cut and fill are given consecutive numbers for recording purposes.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Scaled plans and sections of individual features are all drawn on site; black-and-white and colour photographs of them are taken; and recording sheets are filled in, describing the context of each feature.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] All this information serves as a permanent record of the now-destroyed archaeology and is used to describe and interpret the site.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Once artifacts and structures have been excavated or collected during surface surveys, they must be studied properly.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This process is known as post-excavation analysis, and is usually the most time-consuming part of an archaeological investigation.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It is not uncommon for final excavation reports for major sites to take years to be published.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] At a basic level of analysis, artifacts found are cleaned, catalogued and compared to published collections.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This comparison process often involves classifying them typologically and identifying other sites with similar artifact assemblages.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] However, a much broader range of analytical techniques is available through archaeological science, allowing artifacts to be dated and their compositions examined.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Bones, plants, and pollen collected from a site can all be analysing using the methods of zooarchaeology, paleoethnobotany, palynology and stable isotopes while any texts can usually be deciphered.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] These techniques frequently provide information that would not otherwise be known, thereby contributing greatly to understanding a site.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] As with most academic disciplines, there are a very large number of archaeological sub-disciplines characterized by a specific method or type of material (e.g., lithic analysis, music, archaeobotany), geographical or chronological focus (e.g.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Near Eastern archaeology, Islamic archaeology, Medieval archaeology), other thematic concern (e.g. maritime archaeology, landscape archaeology, battlefield archaeology), or a specific archaeological culture or civilization (e.g.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Historical archaeology is the study of cultures with some form of writing and deals with objects and issues from the past.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In medieval Europe, archaeologists have explored the illicit burial of unbaptized children in medieval texts and cemeteries.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In downtown New York City, archaeologists have exhumed the 18th century remains of the African Burial Ground.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] When remnants of the WWII Siegfried Line were being destroyed, emergency archaeological digs were conducted whenever any part of the line was removed, to advance scientific knowledge and reveal details of its construction.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Ethnoarchaeology is the ethnographic study of living people, designed to aid in our interpretation of the archaeological record.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The approach first gained prominence during the processual movement of the 1960s, and continues to be a vibrant component of post-processual and other current archaeological approaches.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Early ethnoarchaeological research focused on hunter-gatherer or foraging societies; today, ethnoarchaeological research encompasses a much wider range of human behaviour.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Experimental archaeology represents the application of the experimental method to develop more highly controlled observations of processes that create and impact the archaeological record.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In the context of the logical positivism of processualism with its goals of improving the scientific rigor of archaeological epistemologies, the experimental method gained importance.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Experimental techniques remain a crucial component to improving the inferential frameworks for interpreting the archaeological record.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeometry aims to systematize archaeological measurement.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It emphasizes the application of analytical techniques from physics, chemistry, and engineering.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It is a field of research that frequently focuses on determining the chemical composition of archaeological remains for source analysis.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeometry also investigates different spatial characteristics of features, employing methods such as space syntax techniques and geodesy as well as computer-based tools such as geographic information system technology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Rare earth elements patterns may also be used.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] A relatively nascent subfield is that of archaeological materials, designed to enhance understanding of prehistoric and non-industrial culture through scientific analysis of the structure and properties of materials associated with human activity.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Digital Archeology is an interdisciplinary field that applies information technology (IT), digital tools, and data management techniques to archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] It includes virtual archeology and computational archeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Examples of digital archaeology include the use of computer graphics to create virtual 3D models of sites, like the throne room of an Assyrian palace or ancient Rome.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Photogrammetry and digital topographical models are combined with astronomical calculations to check if structures, such as pillars, align with astronomical events like the sun's position at a solstice.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Agent-based modelling and simulation are used to understand past social dynamics and outcomes.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Data mining is applied to large collections of archaeological 'grey literature'.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Archaeology can be a subsidiary activity within Cultural resource management (CRM), also called Cultural heritage management (CHM) in the UK.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] CRM archaeologists frequently examine archaeological sites threatened by development.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] CRM accounts for most archaeological research done in the US and much of that in western Europe.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In the US, CRM archaeology has been a growing concern since the passage of the National Historic Preservation Act (NHPA) of 1966.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Most scholars and politicians believe CRM has helped preserve much of the US's history and prehistory that would otherwise have been lost to the expansion of cities, dams, and highways.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Along with other statutes, the NHPA mandates that projects on federal land, or involving federal funds or permits, consider the effects of the project on each archaeological site.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The application of CRM in the UK is not limited to government-funded projects.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Since 1990, PPG 16 has required planners to consider archaeology as a material consideration in determining applications for new development.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] As a result, archaeological organizations undertake mitigation work in advance of or during construction in archaeologically sensitive areas, at the developer's expense.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Some of the largest archaeological projects ever undertaken in the UK are due to major infrastructure projects such as the A14 road improvement scheme and the construction of HS2.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In England, ultimate responsibility of care for the historic environment rests with the Department for Culture, Media and Sport in association with English Heritage.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, the same responsibilities lie with Historic Scotland, Cadw and the Northern Ireland Environment Agency respectively.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] In France, the Institut national du patrimoine (The National Institute of Cultural Heritage) trains curators specialized in archaeology.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Their mission is to enhance the objects discovered.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The curator is the link between scientific knowledge, administrative regulations, heritage objects, and the public.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Among the goals of CRM are the identification, preservation, and maintenance of cultural sites on public and private lands, and the removal of culturally valuable materials from areas where they would otherwise be destroyed by human activity, such as proposed construction.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This study examines whether significant archaeological sites are present in the area affected by the proposed construction.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] If these do exist, time and money must be allotted for their excavation.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] If initial survey and/or test excavations indicate the presence of an extraordinarily valuable site, the construction may be prohibited entirely.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Cultural resources management has been criticized.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] CRM is conducted by private companies that bid for projects by submitting proposals outlining the work to be done and the expected budget.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The agency responsible for the construction often chooses the proposal that asks for the least funding.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] CRM archaeologists face time pressure, often forced to complete their work in much less time than might be allotted to a purely academic project.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Compounding the time pressure is the vetting process for site reports that CRM firms are required to submit to the appropriate State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO).
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] From the SHPO's perspective, there is no difference between a report submitted by a CRM firm operating under a tight deadline and a multi-year academic project.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The ratio of open academic archaeology positions to the number of archaeology MA/MSc and PhD students is low.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] CRM, once an intellectual backwater for individuals with "strong backs and weak minds", has attracted these graduates, and CRM offices are increasingly staffed by advance degreed workers with a track record of producing scholarly articles, but who also have extensive CRM field experience.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The protection of archaeological finds for the public from catastrophes, wars, and armed conflicts is increasingly being implemented internationally.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This happens, on the one hand, through international agreements and, on the other hand, through organizations that monitor or enforce protection.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] United Nations, UNESCO, and Blue Shield International deal with the protection of cultural heritage, including archaeological sites.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This also applies to the integration of United Nations peacekeeping.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Blue Shield International has undertaken various fact-finding missions in recent years to protect archaeological sites during the wars in Libya, Syria, Egypt, and Lebanon.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The importance of archaeological finds for identity, tourism, and sustainable economic growth is repeatedly emphasized internationally.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The president of Blue Shield International, Karl von Habsburg, said during a cultural property protection mission in Lebanon in April 2019 with the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon: "Cultural assets are part of the identity of the people who live in a certain place.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] If you destroy their culture, you also destroy their identity.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Early archaeology was largely an attempt to uncover spectacular artifacts and features or to explore vast, mysterious abandoned cities, and was mostly carried out by upper-class, scholarly men.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] This general tendency laid the foundation for the modern popular view of archaeology and archaeologists.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Many of the public view archaeology as something only available to a narrow demographic.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] The job of archaeologist is depicted as a "romantic adventurist occupation", and as a hobby more than a job in the scientific community.
[src:anthropologist/archaeologist-p01] Cinema audiences form a notion of "who archaeologists are, why they do what they do, and how relationships to the past are constituted", and are often under the impression that all archaeology takes place in a distant and foreign land, only to collect monetarily or spiritually priceless artifacts.
